{"title_page": "Rochester, Kent", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n | official_name        = Rochester\n | static_image_name    = 2006SweepsCath1crop.jpg\n | static_image_caption = [[Rochester Cathedral]] viewed from the west at Castle Gardens\n | unitary_england      = [[Medway]]\n | lieutenancy_england  = [[Kent]]\n | region               = South East England\n | country              = England\n | coordinates          = {{coord|51.375|0.500|display=inline,title}}\n | population           = 62,982\n | population_ref       = (2011 Census)<ref name=\"nomisweb.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/sources/census_2011_ks/report?compare=1119885152|title=Custom report - Nomis - Official Labour Market Statistics|website=www.nomisweb.co.uk}}</ref>\n | constituency_westminster = [[Rochester & Strood (UK Parliament constituency)|Rochester & Strood]]\n | post_town            = ROCHESTER\n | postcode_area        = ME\n | postcode_district    = ME1, ME2\n | dial_code            = 01634\n | os_grid_reference    = TQ739684\n | london_distance      =\n}}\n\n'''Rochester''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|r|\u0252|t\u0283|\u026a|s|t|\u0259r}} {{respell|ROTCH|iss|t\u0259r}}) is a town and was a historic [[City status in the United Kingdom|city]] in the [[unitary authority]] of [[Medway]] in [[Kent]], England. It is at the [[lowest bridging point]] of the [[River Medway]] about {{convert|30|mi|km|sigfig=1}} from [[London]].\n\nRochester was for many years a favourite of [[Charles Dickens]], who owned nearby [[Gads Hill Place]], [[Higham, Kent|Higham]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discovergravesham.co.uk/higham/gads-hill-place.html|title=Gads Hill Place - Discover Gravesham|website=www.discovergravesham.co.uk}}</ref> basing many of his novels on the area. The [[Diocese of Rochester]], the second oldest in [[England]], is centred on [[Rochester Cathedral]] and was responsible for the founding of [[King's School, Rochester|a school, now ''The King's School'']] in 604 AD,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kings-rochester.co.uk/|title=King's Rochester - First Rate Independent Education|website=www.kings-rochester.co.uk}}</ref> which is recognised as being the [[List of the oldest schools in the world|second oldest continuously running school in the world]]. [[Rochester Castle]], built by [[Gundulf of Rochester|Bishop Gundulf of Rochester]], has one of the best preserved [[keep]]s in either England or France, and during the [[First Barons' War]] (1215\u20131217) in [[John, King of England|King John's]] reign, baronial forces captured the castle from [[Stephen Langton|Archbishop Stephen Langton]] and held it against the king, who then besieged it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.english-heritage.org.uk/server/show/nav.14818 |title=English Heritage Rochester Castle |publisher=English-heritage.org.uk |date= |accessdate=1 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nRochester and its neighbours, [[Chatham, Kent|Chatham]] and [[Gillingham, Kent|Gillingham]], [[Strood]] and a number of outlying villages form a single [[conurbation|large urban area]] known as the [[Medway Towns]] with a population of about 250,000. These places nowadays make up the [[Medway]] Unitary Authority area. It was, until 1998,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medway.gov.uk/index/leisure/localhistory/timeline/17909.htm |title=Medway Council \u2013 Local history: Medway in the 20th century 1901 \u2013 2000 |work=web.archive.org |year=2009 |accessdate=9 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090309021853/http://www.medway.gov.uk/index/leisure/localhistory/timeline/17909.htm |archivedate=9 March 2009 }}</ref> under the control of [[Kent County Council]] and is still part of the [[ceremonial counties of England|ceremonial county]] of [[Kent]], under the latest [[Lieutenancies Act 1997|Lieutenancies Act]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1997/23/schedule/1 |title=Lieutenancies Act 1997  |work=legislation.gov.uk |year=2012 |accessdate=9 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Toponymy==\nThe [[Romano-British]] name for Rochester was [[Durobrivae (Rochester)|Durobrivae]], later Durobrivis c. 730 and Dorobrevis in 844. The two commonly cited origins of this name are that it either came from \"stronghold by the bridge(s)\"<ref name=Glover>The Place names of Kent. Judith Glover. 1976 Batsford. 1982 Meresborough Books. {{ISBN|0-905270-61-4}}</ref> or is the latinisation of the British word ''Dourbruf'' meaning \"swiftstream\".<ref name=Kellys>\nKelly's Directory of Rochester 1951.</ref> Durobrivis was pronounced 'Robrivis. In later times, the word ''[[caester|c\u00e6ster]]'' (=castle, from Latin ''castrum'') was added to the name and the city was called ''Robrivis C\u00e6ster''. [[Bede]] mentions the city in ca. 730 and calls it ''Hrofes c\u00e6ster'', mistaking its meaning as Hrofi's fortified camp. From this we get c. 730 Hrof\u00e6sc\u00e6stre, 811 Hrofescester, 1086 Rovescester, 1610 Rochester.<ref name=Glover/> The Latinised adjective 'Roffensis' refers to Rochester.<ref name=Kellys/><!-- Should be in history- but that is fairly full and should only be a synopsis of the main article-- see [[Wikipedia:WikiProject UK geography/How to write about settlements]] for guidance-->\n\n==History==\n{{main|History of Rochester, Kent}}\n\n[[File:Eastgate House, Rochester, Kent - geograph.org.uk - 1582490.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.95|Eastgate House, Rochester, Kent]]\nNeolithic remains have been found in the vicinity of Rochester; over time it has been variously occupied by [[Celts]], [[Ancient Rome|Romans]], [[Jutes]] and/or [[Saxons]]. During the Celtic period it was one of the two administrative centres of the Cantiaci tribe. During the [[Roman conquest of Britain]] a decisive battle was fought at the Medway somewhere near Rochester.  The first bridge was subsequently constructed early in the Roman period.  During the later Roman period the settlement was walled in stone. [[\u00c6thelberht of Kent|King Ethelbert of Kent]] (560\u2013616) established a legal system which has been preserved in the 12th century ''[[Textus Roffensis]]''.  In AD 604 the bishopric and cathedral were founded.  During this period, from the recall of the legions until the [[Norman conquest]], Rochester was sacked at least twice and besieged on another occasion.\n\nThe [[Middle Ages|medieval period]] saw the building of the current cathedral (1080\u20131130, 1227 and 1343), the building of two castles and the establishment of a significant town.  Rochester Castle saw action in the sieges of 1215 and 1264. Its basic street plan was set out, constrained by the river, Watling Street, Rochester Priory and the [[Rochester Castle|castle]].\n\nRochester has produced two martyrs: [[John Fisher|St John Fisher]], executed by [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]] for refusing to sanction the divorce of [[Catherine of Aragon]]; and [[Nicholas Ridley (martyr)|Bishop Nicholas Ridley]], executed by [[Mary I of England|Queen Mary]] for being an [[English Reformation]] [[protestant]].\n\nThe city was raided by the Dutch as part of the [[Second Anglo-Dutch War]].  The Dutch, commanded by [[de Ruijter|Admiral de Ruijter]], broke through the [[Coastal defence and fortification|chain]] at [[Upnor]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fortified-places.com/upnor.html|title=Fortified Places > Fortresses > Upnor Castle|website=www.fortified-places.com}}</ref> and sailed to Rochester Bridge capturing part of the English fleet and burning it.<ref name=Dutch>*The Dutch Raid, published by the City of Rochester Society 1998.</ref>\n\n[[File:Rochester Castle engraved by H.Adlard after G.F.Sargent. c1836 edited.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.2|Rochester Castle from across the [[River Medway|Medway]] (engraving, G.F. Sargent c. 1836)]]\n\n===Military history===\n{{further|The Nore}}\nRochester has for centuries been of great strategic importance through its position near the confluence of the [[River Thames|Thames]] and the [[River Medway|Medway]]. [[Rochester Castle]] was built to guard the river crossing, and the Royal Dockyard's establishment at [[Chatham, Kent|Chatham]] witnessed the beginning of the [[Royal Navy]]'s long period of supremacy. The town, as part of Medway, is surrounded by two circles of [[fortress]]es; the inner line built during the [[Napoleonic wars]] consists of [[Fort Clarence]], [[Fort Pitt, Kent|Fort Pitt]], [[Fort Amherst]] and [[Fort Gillingham]]. The outer line of [[Henry John Temple, 3rd Viscount Palmerston|Palmerston Forts]] was built during the 1860s in light of the report by the [[Royal Commission on the Defence of the United Kingdom]] and consists of [[Fort Borstal]], [[Fort Bridgewood]], [[Fort Luton]], and the [[Twydall|Twydall Redoubts]], with two additional forts on islands in the Medway, namely [[Fort Hoo]] and [[Fort Darnet]].\n\nDuring the [[First World War]] the [[Short Brothers]]' [[Fixed-wing aircraft|aircraft]] manufacturing company developed the first plane to launch a torpedo, the [[Short Type 184|Short Admiralty Type 184]], at its seaplane factory on the River Medway not far from Rochester Castle. In the intervening period between the 20th century World Wars the company established a world-wide reputation as a constructor of flying boats with aircraft such as the [[Short Singapore|Singapore]], [[Short Empire|Empire]] 'C'-Class and [[Short Sunderland|Sunderland]]. During the [[Second World War]], Shorts also designed and manufactured the first four-engined [[bomber]], the [[Short Stirling|Stirling]].\n\nThe [[UK]]'s decline in naval power and shipbuilding competitiveness led to the government decommissioning the RN Shipyard at Chatham in 1984, which led to the subsequent demise of much local maritime industry. Rochester and its neighbouring communities were hit hard by this and have experienced a painful adjustment to a [[post-industrial economy]], with much social deprivation and unemployment resulting. On the closure of Chatham Dockyard the area experienced an unprecedented surge in unemployment to 24%; this had dropped to 2.4% of the local population by 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-kent-26793760|title=Chatham Dockyard closure 'very positive for the area'|date=31 March 2014|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n===Civic history and traditions===\nRochester was recognised as a City from 1211 to 1998. The City of Rochester's ancient status was unique, as it had no formal council or Charter Trustees nor a Mayor, instead having the office of Admiral of the River Medway '''hi'''''Italic text'', whose incumbent acted as ''de facto'' civic leader.<ref name=\"LondonGazette48875\">{{London Gazette|issue=48875|page=1173|date=28 January 1982}} Publishing Letters Patent dated 25 January 1982, text also available from [http://cityark.medway.gov.uk/ Medway Council archives website]</ref>\n\nSince Norman times Rochester had always governed land on the other side of the [[River Medway|Medway]] in [[Strood]], which was known as ''Strood [[Intra (disambiguation)|Intra]]''; before 1835 it was about {{convert|100|yards}} wide and stretched to Gun Lane. In the [[1835 Municipal Corporations Act]] the boundaries were extended to include more of Strood and Frindsbury, and part of Chatham known as ''Chatham Intra''.\n\nLike many of the mediaeval towns of England, Rochester had civic [[Freedom of the City|Freemen]] whose historic duties and rights were abolished by the [[Municipal Corporations Act 1835]]. However, the ''[[Guild]] of Free Fishers and Dredgers'' continues to the present day and retains rights, duties and responsibilities on the Medway, between Sheerness and Hawkwood Stone.<ref>[http://www.freemen-few.org.uk/UserControls/FCKEditor/.../ROCHESTER.doc ]{{dead link|date=July 2018}}</ref> This ancient corporate body convenes at the Admiralty Court whose [[Jury]] of Freemen is responsible for the conservancy of the River as enshrined in current legislation. The City Freedom can be obtained by residents after serving a period of \"servitude\", i.e. [[apprenticeship]] (traditionally seven years), before admission as a Freeman. The annual ceremonial [[beating the bounds|Beating of the Bounds]] by the River Medway takes place after the Admiralty Court, usually on the first Saturday of July.\n\n===Ecclesiastical parishes===\n[[File:Diocese of Rochester arms.svg|thumb|right|upright=0.5|Arms of diocese of Rochester]]{{for| parishes in the wider Rochester area |Strood#Churches|Frindsbury#The Church of All Saints}}\nThere were three medieval [[parish]]es: St Nicholas', [[St. Margaret's Church, Rochester|St Margaret's]] and St Clement's.  St Clement's was in Horsewash Lane until the last vicar died in 1538 when it was joined with St Nicholas' parish;  the church's last remaining foundations were finally removed when the railway was being constructed in the 1850s. [[St Nicholas' Church, Rochester|St Nicholas' Church]] was built in 1421 beside the [[Rochester Cathedral|cathedral]] to serve as a parish church for the citizens of Rochester.  The ancient cathedral included the [[Benedictine monastery|Benedictine monastic]] [[priory]] of [[St Andrew]] with greater status than the local parishes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/kent/vol2/pp121-126|title=Houses of Benedictine monks: The cathedral priory of St Andrew, Rochester - British History Online|website=www.british-history.ac.uk}}</ref> Rochester's pre-1537 diocese, under the jurisdiction of the Church of Rome, covered a vast area extending into East Anglia and included all of Essex.<ref>[https://www.churchofengland.org/media/40668/chapter2.pdf www.churchofengland.org][</ref>\n\nAs a result of the restructuring of the Church during the [[Protestant Reformation|Reformation]] the cathedral was reconsecrated as the ''Cathedral Church of Christ and the Blessed Virgin Mary'' without [[parish church|parochial]] responsibilities, being a diocesan church.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rochestercathedral.org/services/weddings |title=Weddings |publisher=Rochester Cathedral |accessdate=2 September 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722131045/http://www.rochestercathedral.org/services/weddings |archive-date=22 July 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In the 19th century the parish of St Peter's was created to serve the burgeoning city with the new church being consecrated in 1859. Following demographic shifts, St Peter's and St Margaret's were recombined as a joint benefice in 1953 with the parish of St Nicholas with St Clement being absorbed in 1971.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parishofrochester.co.uk/Our%20Parish.htm |title=St Margaret's Parish |accessdate=9 September 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402090607/http://www.parishofrochester.co.uk/Our%20Parish.htm |archive-date=2 April 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The combined parish is now the \"Parish of St Peter with St Margaret\", centred at the new (1973) Parish Centre in The Delce (St Peter's) with St Margaret's remaining as a [[Chapel of Ease|chapel-of-ease]]. Old St Peter's was demolished in 1974, while St Nicholas' Church has been converted into the diocesan offices but remains consecrated. Continued expansion south has led to the creation of an additional more recent parish of St Justus (1956) covering The Tideway [[housing estate|estate]] and surrounding area.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rochester.anglican.org/churches/rad/rochester/rochester/parish-details.htm#st_margaret/index.htm |title=Rochester Diocese |publisher=Rochester.anglican.org |accessdate=2 September 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926204818/http://www.rochester.anglican.org/churches/rad/rochester/rochester/parish-details.htm#st_margaret/index.htm#st_margaret/index.htm |archive-date=26 September 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nA church dedicated to St Mary the Virgin at [[City gate|Eastgate]], which was of Anglo-Saxon foundation, is understood to have constituted a parish until the Middle Ages, but few records survive.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rbt.org.uk/news/2012/newsitem17.htm|title=www.rbt.org.uk|access-date=5 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924084945/http://www.rbt.org.uk/news/2012/newsitem17.htm|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Governance==\nOn 1 April 1974, the City Council was abolished under the [[Local Government Act 1972]], and the territory was merged with the [[District of Medway]], [[Chatham, Kent|Borough of Chatham]] and most of [[Strood Rural District]], including the parishes of [[Cuxton]], [[Halling, Kent|Halling]] and [[Cliffe-at-Hoo|Cliffe]], and the [[Hoo Peninsula]], to form a new a [[local government district]] called the [[Borough of Medway]], within the county of Kent. [[Medway Borough Council]] applied to inherit Rochester's city status, but this was refused; instead [[letters patent]] were granted constituting the area of the former Rochester local government district to be the City of Rochester, to \"perpetuate the ancient name\" and to recall \"the long history and proud heritage of the said City\".<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=46243|page=3651|date=21 March 1974}} Letters Patent dated 18 March 1974, text also available from [http://cityark.medway.gov.uk/ Medway Council archives website]</ref> The [[Home Office]] said that the city status may be extended to the entire borough if it had \"Rochester\" in its name, so in 1979, Medway Borough Council renamed the borough to [[Borough of Rochester-upon-Medway]], and in 1982, Rochester's city status was transferred to the entire borough by letters patent, with the district being called the [[City of Rochester-upon-Medway]].<ref name=\"LondonGazette48875\"/> The [[Admiral]] of the River Medway was ''ex-officio'' Mayor of Rochester and this dignity transferred to the Mayor of Medway when that unitary authority was created, along with the Admiralty Court for the River which constitutes a committee of the Council.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medway.gov.uk/thecouncilanddemocracy/mayor/civicfunctions.aspx|title=www.medway.gov.uk|access-date=21 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141221173032/http://www.medway.gov.uk/thecouncilanddemocracy/mayor/civicfunctions.aspx|archive-date=21 December 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n[[File:GuildhallRochester.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.9|<center>[[Rochester Guildhall|The Guildhall]], Rochester</center>]]\n\nOn 1 April 1998, the existing local government districts of Rochester-upon-Medway and [[Gillingham, Kent|Gillingham]] were abolished and became the new [[unitary authority]] of [[Medway]]. The [[Department of Environment, Transport and the Regions]] informed the city council that since it was the [[local government district]] that officially held City status under the 1982 Letters Patent, the council would need to appoint [[charter trustees]] to preserve its city status, but the outgoing [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]-run council decided not to appoint \"[[Charter Trustees]]\", so the city status was lost when Rochester-upon-Medway was abolished as a local government district.<ref name=\"Error costs Rochester city status\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/1991827.stm |title=Error costs Rochester city status |work=BBC News |date=16 May 2002 |accessdate=2 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/kent/7511023.stm |title=Town seeks to regain city status |work=BBC News |date=17 July 2008 |accessdate=2 September 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"EasternDaily\">{{cite news|url=http://www.edp24.co.uk/news/medway_city_bid_aims_to_bring_city_status_back_to_the_area_1_924248|date=1 June 2011|publisher=[[Archant Community Media]]|newspaper=[[Eastern Daily Press]]|accessdate=11 April 2015|url-status=dead|archivedate=11 April 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150411143415/http://www.edp24.co.uk/news/medway_city_bid_aims_to_bring_city_status_back_to_the_area_1_924248|title=Medway City bid aims to bring city status back to the area|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Bowen2003\">{{cite report|first=Mark|url=http://democracy.medway.gov.uk/data/regeneration%20&%20community%20overview%20and%20scrutiny%20committee/20030304/agenda/report%20(agenda%20item%205)%203.pdf|url-status=live|accessdate=11 April 2015|archivedate=27 October 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141027004924/http://democracy.medway.gov.uk/Data/Regeneration%20%26%20Community%20Overview%20and%20Scrutiny%20Committee/20030304/Agenda/Report%20%28Agenda%20item%205%29%203.pdf|date=4 March 2004|title=Rochester City Status|publisher=[[Medway Council]]|last=Bowen|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Hicks2010\">{{cite report|last=Hicks|first=Richard|url=http://democracy.medway.gov.uk/mgconvert2pdf.aspx?id=6327|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150411144234/http://democracy.medway.gov.uk/mgconvert2pdf.aspx?id=6327|accessdate=11 April 2015|archivedate=11 April 2015|url-status=live|title=City Status Report|publisher=Medway Council|date=25 November 2010}}</ref> The other local government districts with City status that were abolished around this time, [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]] and [[Hereford]], decided to appoint [[Charter Trustees]] to maintain the existence of their own cities and the mayoralties. The incoming Medway Council apparently only became aware of this when, in 2002, it was advised that Rochester was not on the [[Lord Chancellor's Office]]'s list of cities.<ref>[http://democracy.medway.gov.uk/Data/Regeneration%20&%20Community%20Overview%20and%20Scrutiny%20Committee/20030304/Agenda/Report%20(Agenda%20item%205)%203.pdf Medway Council \u2013 Regeneration and Community Overview and Scrutiny Committee, Report on Rochester City Status], 4 March 2003.</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Medway Council started to refer to the \"City of Medway\" in promotional material, but it was rebuked and instructed not to do so in future by the [[Advertising Standards Authority (United Kingdom)|Advertising Standards Authority]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.asa.org.uk/Rulings/Adjudications/2011/3/Medway-Council/TF_ADJ_49924.aspx |title= Adjudication on Medway Council |publisher= Advertising Standards Authority |date=16 March 2011 |accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> Subsequently, the Medway Unitary Authority has applied for City status for Medway as a whole, rather than merely for Rochester. Medway applied unsuccessfully for City status in 2000 and 2002 and again in the Queen's Diamond Jubilee Year of 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/kent/8585429.stm |title=Medway Council in Kent makes bid for 2012 city status |work=BBC News |date=24 March 2010 |accessdate=2 September 2011}}</ref> Any future bid to regain formal City status has been recommended to be made under the aegis of '''''Rochester-upon-Medway'''''.\n\nThe 2011 definition of Rochester includes [[Strood]] to the northwest and is defined as an urban subdivision with a 2011 population of 62,982.<ref name=\"nomisweb.co.uk\"/>\n\n[[Kelly Tolhurst]] [[Member of parliament|MP]] is the current parliamentary representative for [[Rochester and Strood (UK Parliament constituency)|the constituency]].\n\n==Geography==\n{{Further|Geography of Kent}}\nRochester lies within the area, known to [[geologist]]s, as the [[London Basin]]. The low-lying [[Hoo peninsula]] to the north of the town consists of [[London Clay]], and the [[alluvium]] brought down by the two rivers\u2014the [[River Thames|Thames]] and the [[River Medway|Medway]]\u2014whose confluence is in this area. The land rises from the river, and being on the dip slope of the [[North Downs]], this consists of [[chalk]] surmounted by the Blackheath Beds of sand and gravel.\n\nAs a [[human settlement]], Rochester became established as the lowest river crossing of the River Medway, well before the arrival of the Romans.\n\nIt is a focal point between two routes, being part of the main route connecting London with the Continent and the north-south routes following the course of the Medway connecting [[Maidstone]] and the [[Weald of Kent]] with the Thames and the North Sea. The Thames Marshes were an important source of [[Sea salt|salt]]. Rochester's roads follow north Kent's valleys and ridges of steep-sided [[chalk]] [[bourne (stream)|bournes]]. There are four ways out of town to the south: up Star Hill, via [[Dairy|The Delce]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/survey-kent/vol4/pp153-182|title=The city and liberty of Rochester: The city parishes - British History Online|website=www.british-history.ac.uk}}</ref> along the Maidstone Road or through [[Borstal, Kent|Borstal]]. The town is inextricably linked with the neighbouring [[Medway Towns]] but separated from [[Maidstone]] by a protective [[ridge]] known as the [[North Downs|Downs]], a designated [[area of Outstanding Natural Beauty]].\n\nAt its most limited geographical size, Rochester is defined as the market town within the [[city wall]]s, now associated with the historic medieval city. However, Rochester historically also included the ancient [[Ward (electoral subdivision)|wards]] of Strood Intra on the river's west bank, and Chatham Intra as well as the three old [[Parish (Church of England)|parishes]] on the Medway's east bank.\n\nThe [[diocese of Rochester]] is another geographical entity which can be referred to as Rochester.\n<!-- Within the city boundaries are several distinct areas: the town centre near the parish church and along the High Street; The Delce area; Strood estate constructed in 1927;\n\n{{Geographic location\n|title ='''Neighbouring areas of Rochester'''\n|Northwest = [[Strood]]\n|North = ''[[Hoo Peninsula]]''\n|Northeast = [[Chatham]]\n|West = [[Gravesend]]\n|Centre = Rochester\n|East = [[Gillingham, Kent]]\n|Southwest = [[Cuxton]] and [[Halling]]\n|South = [[Rochester Airport]] and [[Maidstone]]\n|Southeast = [[Walderslade, Kent]]\n}}\n\nOther nearby localities:\n*[[Chattenden]]\n*[[Cliffe]]\n*[[Cobham Park]]\n*[[Cooling]]\n*[[Hoo St Werbergh]]\n*[[Rainham, Kent]]\n-->\n\n==Climate==\nRochester has an [[oceanic climate]] similar to much of southern England, being accorded [[K\u00f6ppen Climate Classification|K\u00f6ppen Climate Classification-subtype]] of \"[[Oceanic climate|Cfb]]\" (Marine West Coast Climate).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather-summary.php3?s=68730&cityname=Gravesend,+England,+United+Kingdom&units=|title=Gravesend, England K\u00f6ppen Climate Classification (Weatherbase)|website=Weatherbase}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 August 2003, neighbouring [[Gravesend]] recorded one of the highest temperatures since meteorogical records began in the [[United Kingdom]], with a reading of 38.1 degrees Celsius (100.6 degrees Fahrenheit),<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/august/10/newsid_3910000/3910801.stm 2003: Britain swelters in record heat]. http://www.bbc.co.uk 10 August 2003. Retrieved on 28 January 2012.</ref> only beaten by [[Brogdale]], near [[Faversham]], {{convert|22|mi|km|0}} to the ESE.<ref>[http://www.metoffice.com/climate/uk/2003/ 2003 weather summaries] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030220163131/http://www.metoffice.com/climate/uk/2003/ |date=20 February 2003 }}. Met Office. Retrieved on 28 January 2012.</ref> The weather station at Brogdale is run by a volunteer, only reporting its data once a month, whereas [[Gravesend]], which has an official Met Office site at the PLA pilot station,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/public/weather/forecast/u10k8kx5v|title=Gravesend weather forecast|website=Met Office}}</ref> reports data hourly.\n\nBeing near the mouth of the Thames Estuary with the North Sea, Rochester is relatively close to [[continental Europe]] and enjoys a somewhat less temperate climate than other parts of Kent and most of East Anglia. It is therefore less cloudy, drier and less prone to [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]] [[Low-pressure area|depressions]] with their associated wind and rain than western regions of Britain, as well as being hotter in summer and colder in winter. Rochester city centre's micro-climate is more accurately reflected by these officially recorded figures than by readings taken at Rochester Airport.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rochester-airport.co.uk/|title=www.rochester-airport.co.uk|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nNorth and [[North West Kent]] continue to record higher temperatures in [[summer]], sometimes being the hottest area of the country, ''eg.'' on the warmest day of 2011, when temperatures reached 33.1 degrees.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-13936256 | work=BBC News | title=Flash flood warnings for parts of England | date=27 June 2011}}</ref> Additionally, it holds at least two records for the year 2010, of 30.9 degrees<ref>[http://news.uk.msn.com/uk/articles.aspx?cp-documentid=153946459&ocid=today 27 June 2010 Britain basks, but showers due] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131226192412/http://news.uk.msn.com/uk/articles.aspx?cp-documentid=153946459&ocid=today |date=26 December 2013 }}. http://www.news.uk.msn.com {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140928104406/http://news.uk.msn.com/ |date=28 September 2014 }} (28 June 2010). Retrieved on 28 January 2012.</ref> and 31.7 degrees C.<ref>Attewill, Fred. (14 October 2011) [http://www.metro.co.uk/news/834794-weekend-hot-weather-saw-brits-flocking-to-the-beaches Weekend hot weather saw Brits flocking to the beaches]. Metro.co.uk. Retrieved on 28 January 2012.</ref> Another record was set during England's Indian summer of 2011 with 29.9 degrees C., the highest temperature ever recorded in the UK for October.\n\n{{Weather box|location = Stanford-le-Hope (nearest climate station to Gravesend) 1981\u20132010\n|metric first = Yes\n|single line = Yes\n|Jan high C = 7.9\n|Feb high C = 8.0\n|Mar high C = 10.9\n|Apr high C = 13.2\n|May high C = 16.8\n|Jun high C = 19.9\n|Jul high C = 22.1\n|Aug high C = 22.2\n|Sep high C = 19.4\n|Oct high C = 15.2\n|Nov high C = 10.8\n|Dec high C = 8.1\n|year high C = \n|Jan low C = 2.2\n|Feb low C = 1.6\n|Mar low C = 3.3\n|Apr low C = 4.7\n|May low C = 7.5\n|Jun low C = 10.5\n|Jul low C = 13.0\n|Aug low C = 12.5\n|Sep low C = 10.3\n|Oct low C = 7.4\n|Nov low C = 4.4\n|Dec low C = 2.4\n|year low C = \n|Jan precipitation mm = 47.9\n|Feb precipitation mm = 36.7\n|Mar precipitation mm = 37.6\n|Apr precipitation mm = 40.9\n|May precipitation mm = 48.0\n|Jun precipitation mm = 41.1\n|Jul precipitation mm = 52.5\n|Aug precipitation mm = 44.8\n|Sep precipitation mm = 45.5\n|Oct precipitation mm = 64.9\n|Nov precipitation mm = 57.8\n|Dec precipitation mm = 53.8\n|year precipitation mm = \n|Jan sun = 60.0\n|Feb sun = 77.7\n|Mar sun = 113.4\n|Apr sun = 161.5\n|May sun = 194.3\n|Jun sun = 198.7\n|Jul sun = 208.7\n|Aug sun = 195.5\n|Sep sun = 151.1\n|Oct sun = 117.9\n|Nov sun = 74.0\n|Dec sun = 48.6\n|year sun = \n|source 1 = [[Met Office]]}}\n\n==Buildings==\n\nRochester comprises numerous important historic buildings, the most prominent of which are the [[Guildhall]], the [[Corn Exchange]], [[Restoration House]], Eastgate House, as well as [[Rochester Castle]] and [[Rochester Cathedral]]. Many of the town centre's old buildings date from as early as the 14th century up to the 18th century.  The [[chapel]] of [[St. Bartholomew's Hospital, Rochester|St Bartholomew's Hospital]] dates from the ancient priory hospital's foundation in 1078.\n\n==Economy==\n{{See also|Chatham Dockyard}}\n[[File:Rochester2007Dickens0650c.JPG|thumb|<center>'''Rochester High Street'''</center>]]\nThomas Aveling started a small business in 1850 producing and repairing [[List of agricultural machinery|agricultural plant equipment]].  In 1861 this became the firm of [[Aveling and Porter]], which was to become the largest manufacturer of agricultural machinery and [[steamroller|steam roller]]s in the country.<ref name=Shire>*Discovering Traction Engines, \u2013 Harold Bonnett \u2013 Shire Publications (1975) \u2013 {{ISBN|0-85263-318-1}}</ref> Aveling was elected Admiral of the River Medway (i.e. Mayor of Rochester) for 1869-70.\n\n==Culture==\n\n===Sweeps Festival===\nSince 1980 the city has seen the revival of the historic Rochester [[Jack-in-the-Green]] [[May Day]] dancing [[chimney sweeps]] tradition, which had died out in the early 1900s. Though not unique to Rochester (similar sweeps' gatherings were held across southern England, notably in Bristol, Deptford, Whitstable and Hastings), its revival was directly inspired by Dickens' description of the celebration in [[Sketches by Boz]].\n\nThe festival has since grown from a small gathering of local [[Morris dance]] sides to one of the largest in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visitkent.co.uk/events/9580/|title=Search for events, activities and exhibitions across Kent|access-date=21 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141221165116/http://www.visitkent.co.uk/events/9580/|archive-date=21 December 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The festival begins with the \"Awakening of Jack-in-the-Green\" ceremony,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/medway/news/thousands-turn-out-for-sweeps-16739/|title=Thousands turn out for Sweeps Festival|publisher=}}</ref> and continues in Rochester High Street over the May [[Bank Holiday]] weekend.\n\nThere are numerous other festivals in Rochester apart from the Sweeps Festival. The association with Dickens is the theme for Rochester's two Dickens Festivals held annually in June and December.<ref name=\"historic-uk1\">{{cite web|author=Historic uk \u2013 heritage of britain accommodation guide |url= http://www.historic-uk.com/DestinationsUK/Rochester.htm |title=Destinations UK \u2013 Rochester, Kent, England |publisher=Historic UK |date=6 June 2010 |accessdate=1 September 2010}}</ref> [[The Medway Fuse Festival]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fusefestival.org.uk/|title=Fuse Festival \u2013 Come party with us|website=fusefestival.org.uk}}</ref> usually arranges performances in Rochester and the latest festival to take shape is the Rochester Literature Festival, the brainchild of three local writers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rochesterlitfest.com/|title=Rochester Literature Festival|website=Rochester Literature Festival}}</ref>\n\n===Library===\nA new [[public library]] was built alongside the Adult Education Centre, Eastgate. This enabled the registry office to move from Maidstone Road, Chatham into the Corn Exchange on Rochester High Street (where the library was formerly housed). As mentioned in a report presented to Medway Council's ''Community Services Overview and Scrutiny Committee'' on 28 March 2006, the new library opened in late summer (2006).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visitmedway.org/places-of-interest/rochester-library|title=www.visitmedway.org|access-date=21 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141221174118/http://www.visitmedway.org/places-of-interest/rochester-library|archive-date=21 December 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Huguenot Museum===\nA new Huguenot Museum, which includes items from the collections of the [[French Hospital (La Providence)|French Hospital]], was opened in Rochester on 13 May 2015, with support from the Heritage Lottery Fund and individual donations.<ref>Website of the [http://www.huguenotmuseum.org/ Huguenot Museum], Rochester, Kent, located not far from the French Hospital itself.</ref>\n\n===Theatre===\n[[File:2006SweepsSideRochester.JPG|thumb|Sweeps festival in 2006]]\nThere is a small amateur theatre called Medway Little Theatre on St Margaret's Banks next to Rochester High Street opposite the former railway station.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.danwillis.freeserve.co.uk/ |title= Medway Little Theatre |access-date= 31 January 2012 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120416041818/http://www.danwillis.freeserve.co.uk/ |archive-date= 16 April 2012 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref> The theatre was formed out of a creative alliance with the Medway Theatre Club, managed by Marion Martin, at St Luke's Methodist Church on City Way, Rochester<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medwaymethodistchurch.org.uk/stlukesmethodistchurchce.htm|title=St Luke's - Gillingham Methodist Church - NKMC|website=www.medwaymethodistchurch.org.uk|access-date=28 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141228232049/http://www.medwaymethodistchurch.org.uk/stlukesmethodistchurchce.htm|archive-date=28 December 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> between 1985 and 1988, since when drama and theatre studies have become well established in Rochester owing to the dedication of the Medway Theatre Club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.danwillis.freeserve.co.uk/stoppress.htm|title=''Medway Theatre Club''|access-date=28 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141222213208/http://www.danwillis.freeserve.co.uk/stoppress.htm|archive-date=22 December 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Media===\nLocal newspapers for Rochester include the ''Medway Messenger'', published by the [[KM Group]], and free papers.\n\nThe local commercial [[Radio broadcasting|radio station]] for Rochester is [[KMFM Medway]], owned by the KM Group. Medway is also served by community radio station [[Radio Sunlight]] which is now an online service. The area also receives broadcasts from county-wide stations [[BBC Radio Kent]], [[Heart Kent|Heart]] and [[Gold (radio)|Gold]], as well as from various [[Essex]] and [[Greater London]] radio stations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radio-now.co.uk/south.htm#KENT|title=radio-now.co.uk - Kent, Surrey and Sussex radio stations|first=|last=radionow|website=www.radio-now.co.uk}}</ref>\nRochester is part of the [[ITV Meridian]] and [[BBC South East]] area, receiving television signals from the [[Bluebell Hill]] transmitter on the crest of the [[North Downs]] to the SE, supplemented by a low power relay transmitter in central Chatham.\n\n===Sport===\n[[association football|Football]] is played with many teams competing in Saturday and Sunday leagues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leaguewebsite.co.uk/randd/Home|title=Rochester and District Football League - Home Page|website=www.leaguewebsite.co.uk}}</ref> The local football club is [[Rochester United F.C.|Rochester United F.C]]. Rochester F.C. was its old football club but has been defunct for many decades. [[Rugby football|Rugby]] is also played; Medway R.F.C. play their matches at Priestfields and ''Old Williamsonians'' is associated with [[Sir Joseph Williamson's Mathematical School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oldwilliamsonianclub.com/|title=oldwilliamsonianclub.com \u2013 oldwilliamsonianclub.com|website=www.oldwilliamsonianclub.com}}</ref>\n\n[[Cricket]] is played in the town, with teams entered in the [[Kent Cricket League]].\n[[Holcombe Hockey Club]] enter teams in both the [[Men's England Hockey League|Men's]] and [[Women's England Hockey League]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.holcombehc.org.uk/|title=Holcombe Hockey Club|website=www.holcombehc.org.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.englandhockey.co.uk/fl/ehl/tables.asp?section=355/|title=EHL league tables|accessdate=18 March 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141221171444/http://www.englandhockey.co.uk/fl/ehl/tables.asp?section=355%2F|archivedate=21 December 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Motorcycle speedway|Speedway]] was staged on a track adjacent to City Way that opened in 1932. Proposals for a revival in the early 1970s did not materialise and the ''Rochester Bombers'' became the [[Romford Bombers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.national-speedway-museum.co.uk/romform%20speedway%20track.html|title=www.national-speedway-museum.co.uk|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nSailing and rowing are also popular on the River Medway with respective clubs being based in Rochester.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medwayyachtclub.com/|title=Medway Yacht Club|website=Medway Yacht Club}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medwaytownsrowingclub.co.uk/|title=medway-rowing|website=medway-rowing}}</ref>\n\n===Film===\nThe 1959 [[James Bond]] ''[[Goldfinger (novel)|Goldfinger]]'' describes Bond driving along the [[A2 road (Great Britain)|A2]] through the Medway Towns from Strood to Chatham. Of interest is the mention of \"inevitable traffic jams\" on the [[Strood]] side of [[Rochester Bridge]], the novel being written some years prior to the construction of the [[M2 motorway (Great Britain)|M2 motorway]] Medway bypass.\n\nRochester is the setting of the controversial 1965 [[Peter Watkins]] television film ''[[The War Game]]'', which depicts the town's destruction by a nuclear missile.<ref name=WarGame>{{cite web|url=http://www.museum.tv/archives/etv/W/htmlW/wargamethe/wargamethe.htm |title=War Game, The |publisher=Museum.tv |date=31 July 1985 |accessdate=1 September 2010}}</ref> The opening sequence was shot in Chatham Town Hall, but the credits particularly thank the people of [[Dover]], [[Gravesend]] and [[Tonbridge]].\n\nThe 2011 adventure film ''[[Ironclad (film)|Ironclad]]'' is based upon the [[First Barons' War#Sieges of Windsor and Rochester|1215 siege of Rochester Castle]]. There are however [[Ironclad (film)#Fictional elements|areas where the plot differs from accepted historical narrative]].\n\n===Notable people===\n[[File:Rochester High Street looking east.jpg|right|thumb|Rochester High Street]]\n;Charles Dickens:\nThe historic city was for many years the favourite of [[Charles Dickens]], who lived within the diocese at nearby [[Gads Hill Place]], [[Higham, Kent|Higham]], many of his novels being based on the area. Descriptions of the town appear in ''[[Pickwick Papers]]'', ''[[Great Expectations]]'' and (lightly fictionalised as \"Cloisterham\") in ''[[The Mystery of Edwin Drood]]''. Elements of two houses in Rochester, Satis House and [[Restoration House]], are used for [[Miss Havisham]]'s house in ''Great Expectations'', [[Satis House]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OlWQNGB5628C&pg=PA97&lpg=PA97&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Follow These Writers|author= Judith Bastide|page=97|publisher=Author House|date= 1 April 2013}}</ref>\n;Dame Sybil Thorndike and Russell Thorndike:\nThe actress Dame [[Sybil Thorndike]] and her brother [[Russell Thorndike|Russell]] were brought up in Minor Canon Row adjacent to the cathedral; the daughter of a [[Canon (priest)|canon]] of Rochester Cathedral, she was educated at [[Rochester Grammar School for Girls]].  A local doctors' practice,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.thorndike.nhs.uk|title=Dame Sybil Thorndike Practice |accessdate=30 October 2011}}</ref> local dental practice<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.thorndent.co.uk|title=Thorndike Dental Practice |accessdate=30 October 2011}}</ref> and a hall at Rochester Grammar School are all named after her.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thelondonquartet.blogspot.co.uk/2011/06/thorndike-arts-centre-rochester.html|title=Thorndike Arts Centre, Rochester|website=thelondonquartet.blogspot.co.uk}}</ref>\n;Sir Peter Buck:\n[[Peter Buck (mayor)|Sir Peter Buck]] was [[Mayor of Medway|Admiral of the Medway]] in the 17th century; [[knight]]ed in 1603 he and [[William Barlow (bishop of Lincoln)|Bishop Barlow]] hosted [[James VI and I|King James]], the [[House of Stuart|Stuart royal family]] and the [[Christian IV of Denmark|King of Denmark]] in 1606. A [[Honourable Corps of Gentlemen at Arms|civil servant]] to [[Chatham Dockyard|The Royal Dockyard]] and [[Lord High Admiral of the United Kingdom|Lord High Admiral]], Buck lived at [[Eastgate House, Rochester]].\n;Denis Redman:\nMajor-General [[Denis Redman]], a [[World War II]] veteran, was born and raised in Rochester and later became a founder member of [[REME]], head of his Corps and a [[Major-general (United Kingdom)|Major-General in the British Army]].\n;Kelly Brook\nThe [[Model (people)|model]] and actress [[Kelly Brook]] went to Delce Junior School in Rochester and later the [[The Thomas Aveling School|Thomas Aveling School]] (formerly Warren Wood Girls School).\n\n==Education==\n\n{{for|a full list of schools serving Rochester|List of schools in Medway}}\nMedway council run a [[Selective school#United Kingdom|selective system of education]], similar to other local authorities in Kent, but call their [[secondary modern school]]s ''secondary schools''. Almost all secondary schools in Rochester have opted for [[Academy (English school)|academy]] status.\n\nIn 1701, [[Sir Joseph Williamson]] left a bequest to establish the [[Sir Joseph Williamson's Mathematical School|Mathematical School]], a boys' grammar school, also referred to either as ''Rochester Math'' or ''The Math School''.  Unlike earlier educational foundations, such as [[King's School, Rochester|The King's School]], it was not tied to a religious establishment, but was opened for practical instruction of boys in navigation and mathematics.\n\nThe [[University for the Creative Arts]], formerly the Kent Institute of Art & Design, is located on the boundary of Rochester with Chatham.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucreative.ac.uk/rochester|title=University for the Creative Arts - UCA Rochester - UCA|website=University for the Creative Arts}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\n[[File:rochesterrear.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.05|The old [[Rochester railway station|Rochester Station]] (overground): <br>the rail tracks run along a [[viaduct]].]]\n;Road\nRochester is on the [[A2 road (Great Britain)|A2]], which crosses the Medway at [[Rochester Bridge]] \u2013 the route roughly follows the [[ancient trackway|ancient road]] known as [[Watling Street]], first paved by the Romans, but used by earlier Britons for centuries before the Roman invasion. Nowadays vehicular traffic is largely diverted onto the nearby [[M2 motorway (Great Britain)|M2 motorway]].\n[[Watling Street]] passes through the town, and slightly to the south both the [[M2 motorway (Great Britain)|M2 motorway]] and the [[High Speed 1]] railway line bridge the [[River Medway]].\n;Bus\nBus services are operated by [[Arriva Southern Counties]], which took over the locally owned [[Maidstone & District Motor Services|Maidstone & District]] bus company in the 1990s. Other local bus companies including [[Nu-Venture]] provide certain services, some contracted from the local council.\n;Rail\n{{Medway area RDT}}\n[[Rochester railway station]] is on the [[Chatham Main Line]] and the [[North Kent Line]]. [[Strood railway station]] is on the North Kent Line and the [[Medway Valley Line]]; it links to the HS1 high speed line at [[Ebbsfleet International]] giving a running time of 30 minutes into [[St Pancras railway station|St Pancras]]. All services are provided by [[Southeastern (train operating company)|Southeastern]].\n;Air\n[[Rochester Airport, England|Rochester Airport]] began in September 1933 when Rochester City Council purchased some land as the site for a municipal [[airport]]. One month later the aircraft manufacturers [[Short Brothers]] leased the land for test flying. By 1934\u20135 Short Brothers had taken over the site, and moved in some of their personnel from the existing [[seaplane]] works. The inaugural flight into Rochester was from [[Gravesend, Kent|Gravesend]], John Parker flying the Short Brothers [[Short Scion]] G-ACJI.\n\nIn 1979 the lease reverted to the City Council. After giving thorough consideration to closing the airport, [[General Electric Company plc|GEC]] (then comprising [[Marconi Company|Marconi]] and instrument makers [[Elliott Brothers (computer company)|Elliot Automation]]) decided to take over management of the airport. It maintained two grass [[runway|landing strip]]s while releasing some land for light industrial expansion.\n\n==Further reading==\n* R, Marsh, 1976, The Evolution of a City (Medway Borough)\n* F.F. Smith, 1976, A History of Rochester (JHP Reprint) 9780905540009\n\n==See also==\n*[[Rainham, Kent|Rainham]]\n*[[HM Prison Rochester]]\n*[[Rochester and Strood (UK Parliament constituency)]]\n*[[Earl of Rochester]]\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Rochester, Kent}}\n* [http://www.medway.gov.uk Medway Council Official Site]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100329110819/http://www.medway.gov.uk/medwayimages/ Archive Images]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20000816190442/http://www.rochesterairport.flyer.co.uk/ Rochester Airport and British Aviation]\n* [http://www.glentour.freeuk.com/rochester_sweeps_festival.htm Photographs of the Rochester Sweeps Festival]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071024110949/http://video.google.com/videoplay?docid=6380511021213931299 Google video of Morris Dancers] at Sweeps Festival Rochester 1997\n* [http://rochesterlitfest.com/ Rochester Literature Festival]\n* [http://www.rochestercathedral.org/ www.rochestercathedral.org]\n\n{{Medway}}\n{{Kent}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rochester, Kent| ]]\n[[Category:Medway]]\n[[Category:Market towns in Kent]]\n[[Category:Towns in Kent]]\n[[Category:Towns with cathedrals in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n | official_name        = Rochester\n | static_image_name    = 2006SweepsCath1crop.jpg\n | static_image_caption = [[Rochester Cathedral]] viewed from the west at Castle Gardens\n | unitary_england      = [[Medway]]\n | lieutenancy_england  = [[Kent]]\n | region               = South East England\n | country              = England\n | coordinates          = {{coord|51.375|0.500|display=inline,title}}\n | population           = 62,982\n | population_ref       = (2011 Census)<ref name=\"nomisweb.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/sources/census_2011_ks/report?compare=1119885152|title=Custom report - Nomis - Official Labour Market Statistics|website=www.nomisweb.co.uk}}</ref>\n | constituency_westminster = [[Rochester & Strood (UK Parliament constituency)|Rochester & Strood]]\n | post_town            = ROCHESTER\n | postcode_area        = ME\n | postcode_district    = ME1, ME2\n | dial_code            = 01634\n | os_grid_reference    = TQ739684\n | london_distance      =\n}}\n\n'''Rochester''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|r|\u0252|t\u0283|\u026a|s|t|\u0259r}} {{respell|ROTCH|iss|t\u0259r}}) is a town and was a historic [[City status in the United Kingdom|city]] in the [[unitary authority]] of [[Medway]] in [[Kent]], England. It is at the [[lowest bridging point]] of the [[River Medway]] about {{convert|30|mi|km|sigfig=1}} from [[London]].\n\nRochester was for many years a favourite of [[Charles Dickens]], who owned nearby [[Gads Hill Place]], [[Higham, Kent|Higham]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discovergravesham.co.uk/higham/gads-hill-place.html|title=Gads Hill Place - Discover Gravesham|website=www.discovergravesham.co.uk}}</ref> basing many of his novels on the area. The [[Diocese of Rochester]], the second oldest in [[England]], is centred on [[Rochester Cathedral]] and was responsible for the founding of [[King's School, Rochester|a school, now ''The King's School'']] in 604 AD,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kings-rochester.co.uk/|title=King's Rochester - First Rate Independent Education|website=www.kings-rochester.co.uk}}</ref> which is recognised as being the [[List of the oldest schools in the world|second oldest continuously running school in the world]]. [[Rochester Castle]], built by [[Gundulf of Rochester|Bishop Gundulf of Rochester]], has one of the best preserved [[keep]]s in either England or France, and during the [[First Barons' War]] (1215\u20131217) in [[John, King of England|King John's]] reign, baronial forces captured the castle from [[Stephen Langton|Archbishop Stephen Langton]] and held it against the king, who then besieged it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.english-heritage.org.uk/server/show/nav.14818 |title=English Heritage Rochester Castle |publisher=English-heritage.org.uk |date= |accessdate=1 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nRochester and its neighbours, [[Chatham, Kent|Chatham]] and [[Gillingham, Kent|Gillingham]], [[Strood]] and a number of outlying villages form a single [[conurbation|large urban area]] known as the [[Medway Towns]] with a population of about 250,000. These places nowadays make up the [[Medway]] Unitary Authority area. It was, until 1998,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medway.gov.uk/index/leisure/localhistory/timeline/17909.htm |title=Medway Council \u2013 Local history: Medway in the 20th century 1901 \u2013 2000 |work=web.archive.org |year=2009 |accessdate=9 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090309021853/http://www.medway.gov.uk/index/leisure/localhistory/timeline/17909.htm |archivedate=9 March 2009 }}</ref> under the control of [[Kent County Council]] and is still part of the [[ceremonial counties of England|ceremonial county]] of [[Kent]], under the latest [[Lieutenancies Act 1997|Lieutenancies Act]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1997/23/schedule/1 |title=Lieutenancies Act 1997  |work=legislation.gov.uk |year=2012 |accessdate=9 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Toponymy==\nThe [[Romano-British]] name for Rochester was [[Durobrivae (Rochester)|Durobrivae]], later Durobrivis c. 730 and Dorobrevis in 844. The two commonly cited origins of this name are that it either came from \"stronghold by the bridge(s)\"<ref name=Glover>The Place names of Kent. Judith Glover. 1976 Batsford. 1982 Meresborough Books. {{ISBN|0-905270-61-4}}</ref> or is the latinisation of the British word ''Dourbruf'' meaning \"swiftstream\".<ref name=Kellys>\nKelly's Directory of Rochester 1951.</ref> Durobrivis was pronounced 'Robrivis. In later times, the word ''[[caester|c\u00e6ster]]'' (=castle, from Latin ''castrum'') was added to the name and the city was called ''Robrivis C\u00e6ster''. [[Bede]] mentions the city in ca. 730 and calls it ''Hrofes c\u00e6ster'', mistaking its meaning as Hrofi's fortified camp. From this we get c. 730 Hrof\u00e6sc\u00e6stre, 811 Hrofescester, 1086 Rovescester, 1610 Rochester.<ref name=Glover/> The Latinised adjective 'Roffensis' refers to Rochester.<ref name=Kellys/><!-- Should be in history- but that is fairly full and should only be a synopsis of the main article-- see [[Wikipedia:WikiProject UK geography/How to write about settlements]] for guidance-->\n\n==History==\n{{main|History of Rochester, Kent}}\n\n[[File:Eastgate House, Rochester, Kent - geograph.org.uk - 1582490.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.95|Eastgate House, Rochester, Kent]]\nNeolithic remains have been found in the vicinity of Rochester; over time it has been variously occupied by [[Celts]], [[Ancient Rome|Romans]], [[Jutes]] and/or [[Saxons]]. During the Celtic period it was one of the two administrative centres of the Cantiaci tribe. During the [[Roman conquest of Britain]] a decisive battle was fought at the Medway somewhere near Rochester.  The first bridge was subsequently constructed early in the Roman period.  During the later Roman period the settlement was walled in stone. [[\u00c6thelberht of Kent|King Ethelbert of Kent]] (560\u2013616) established a legal system which has been preserved in the 12th century ''[[Textus Roffensis]]''.  In AD 604 the bishopric and cathedral were founded.  During this period, from the recall of the legions until the [[Norman conquest]], Rochester was sacked at least twice and besieged on another occasion.\n\nThe [[Middle Ages|medieval period]] saw the building of the current cathedral (1080\u20131130, 1227 and 1343), the building of two castles and the establishment of a significant town.  Rochester Castle saw action in the sieges of 1215 and 1264. Its basic street plan was set out, constrained by the river, Watling Street, Rochester Priory and the [[Rochester Castle|castle]].\n\nRochester has produced two martyrs: [[John Fisher|St John Fisher]], executed by [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]] for refusing to sanction the divorce of [[Catherine of Aragon]]; and [[Nicholas Ridley (martyr)|Bishop Nicholas Ridley]], executed by [[Mary I of England|Queen Mary]] for being an [[English Reformation]] [[protestant]].\n\nThe city was raided by the Dutch as part of the [[Second Anglo-Dutch War]].  The Dutch, commanded by [[de Ruijter|Admiral de Ruijter]], broke through the [[Coastal defence and fortification|chain]] at [[Upnor]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fortified-places.com/upnor.html|title=Fortified Places > Fortresses > Upnor Castle|website=www.fortified-places.com}}</ref> and sailed to Rochester Bridge capturing part of the English fleet and burning it.<ref name=Dutch>*The Dutch Raid, published by the City of Rochester Society 1998.</ref>\n\n[[File:Rochester Castle engraved by H.Adlard after G.F.Sargent. c1836 edited.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.2|Rochester Castle from across the [[River Medway|Medway]] (engraving, G.F. Sargent c. 1836)]]\n\n===Military history===\n{{further|The Nore}}\nRochester has for centuries been of great strategic importance through its position near the confluence of the [[River Thames|Thames]] and the [[River Medway|Medway]]. [[Rochester Castle]] was built to guard the river crossing, and the Royal Dockyard's establishment at [[Chatham, Kent|Chatham]] witnessed the beginning of the [[Royal Navy]]'s long period of supremacy. The town, as part of Medway, is surrounded by two circles of [[fortress]]es; the inner line built during the [[Napoleonic wars]] consists of [[Fort Clarence]], [[Fort Pitt, Kent|Fort Pitt]], [[Fort Amherst]] and [[Fort Gillingham]]. The outer line of [[Henry John Temple, 3rd Viscount Palmerston|Palmerston Forts]] was built during the 1860s in light of the report by the [[Royal Commission on the Defence of the United Kingdom]] and consists of [[Fort Borstal]], [[Fort Bridgewood]], [[Fort Luton]], and the [[Twydall|Twydall Redoubts]], with two additional forts on islands in the Medway, namely [[Fort Hoo]] and [[Fort Darnet]].\n\nDuring the [[First World War]] the [[Short Brothers]]' [[Fixed-wing aircraft|aircraft]] manufacturing company developed the first plane to launch a torpedo, the [[Short Type 184|Short Admiralty Type 184]], at its seaplane factory on the River Medway not far from Rochester Castle. In the intervening period between the 20th century World Wars the company established a world-wide reputation as a constructor of flying boats with aircraft such as the [[Short Singapore|Singapore]], [[Short Empire|Empire]] 'C'-Class and [[Short Sunderland|Sunderland]]. During the [[Second World War]], Shorts also designed and manufactured the first four-engined [[bomber]], the [[Short Stirling|Stirling]].\n\nThe [[UK]]'s decline in naval power and shipbuilding competitiveness led to the government decommissioning the RN Shipyard at Chatham in 1984, which led to the subsequent demise of much local maritime industry. Rochester and its neighbouring communities were hit hard by this and have experienced a painful adjustment to a [[post-industrial economy]], with much social deprivation and unemployment resulting. On the closure of Chatham Dockyard the area experienced an unprecedented surge in unemployment to 24%; this had dropped to 2.4% of the local population by 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-kent-26793760|title=Chatham Dockyard closure 'very positive for the area'|date=31 March 2014|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n===Civic history and traditions===\nRochester was recognised as a City from 1211 to 1998. The City of Rochester's ancient status was unique, as it had no formal council or Charter Trustees nor a Mayor, instead having the office of Admiral of the River Medway, whose incumbent acted as ''de facto'' civic leader.<ref name=\"LondonGazette48875\">{{London Gazette|issue=48875|page=1173|date=28 January 1982}} Publishing Letters Patent dated 25 January 1982, text also available from [http://cityark.medway.gov.uk/ Medway Council archives website]</ref>\n\nSince Norman times Rochester had always governed land on the other side of the [[River Medway|Medway]] in [[Strood]], which was known as ''Strood [[Intra (disambiguation)|Intra]]''; before 1835 it was about {{convert|100|yards}} wide and stretched to Gun Lane. In the [[1835 Municipal Corporations Act]] the boundaries were extended to include more of Strood and Frindsbury, and part of Chatham known as ''Chatham Intra''.\n\nLike many of the mediaeval towns of England, Rochester had civic [[Freedom of the City|Freemen]] whose historic duties and rights were abolished by the [[Municipal Corporations Act 1835]]. However, the ''[[Guild]] of Free Fishers and Dredgers'' continues to the present day and retains rights, duties and responsibilities on the Medway, between Sheerness and Hawkwood Stone.<ref>[http://www.freemen-few.org.uk/UserControls/FCKEditor/.../ROCHESTER.doc ]{{dead link|date=July 2018}}</ref> This ancient corporate body convenes at the Admiralty Court whose [[Jury]] of Freemen is responsible for the conservancy of the River as enshrined in current legislation. The City Freedom can be obtained by residents after serving a period of \"servitude\", i.e. [[apprenticeship]] (traditionally seven years), before admission as a Freeman. The annual ceremonial [[beating the bounds|Beating of the Bounds]] by the River Medway takes place after the Admiralty Court, usually on the first Saturday of July.\n\n===Ecclesiastical parishes===\n[[File:Diocese of Rochester arms.svg|thumb|right|upright=0.5|Arms of diocese of Rochester]]{{for| parishes in the wider Rochester area |Strood#Churches|Frindsbury#The Church of All Saints}}\nThere were three medieval [[parish]]es: St Nicholas', [[St. Margaret's Church, Rochester|St Margaret's]] and St Clement's.  St Clement's was in Horsewash Lane until the last vicar died in 1538 when it was joined with St Nicholas' parish;  the church's last remaining foundations were finally removed when the railway was being constructed in the 1850s. [[St Nicholas' Church, Rochester|St Nicholas' Church]] was built in 1421 beside the [[Rochester Cathedral|cathedral]] to serve as a parish church for the citizens of Rochester.  The ancient cathedral included the [[Benedictine monastery|Benedictine monastic]] [[priory]] of [[St Andrew]] with greater status than the local parishes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/kent/vol2/pp121-126|title=Houses of Benedictine monks: The cathedral priory of St Andrew, Rochester - British History Online|website=www.british-history.ac.uk}}</ref> Rochester's pre-1537 diocese, under the jurisdiction of the Church of Rome, covered a vast area extending into East Anglia and included all of Essex.<ref>[https://www.churchofengland.org/media/40668/chapter2.pdf www.churchofengland.org][</ref>\n\nAs a result of the restructuring of the Church during the [[Protestant Reformation|Reformation]] the cathedral was reconsecrated as the ''Cathedral Church of Christ and the Blessed Virgin Mary'' without [[parish church|parochial]] responsibilities, being a diocesan church.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rochestercathedral.org/services/weddings |title=Weddings |publisher=Rochester Cathedral |accessdate=2 September 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722131045/http://www.rochestercathedral.org/services/weddings |archive-date=22 July 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In the 19th century the parish of St Peter's was created to serve the burgeoning city with the new church being consecrated in 1859. Following demographic shifts, St Peter's and St Margaret's were recombined as a joint benefice in 1953 with the parish of St Nicholas with St Clement being absorbed in 1971.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parishofrochester.co.uk/Our%20Parish.htm |title=St Margaret's Parish |accessdate=9 September 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402090607/http://www.parishofrochester.co.uk/Our%20Parish.htm |archive-date=2 April 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The combined parish is now the \"Parish of St Peter with St Margaret\", centred at the new (1973) Parish Centre in The Delce (St Peter's) with St Margaret's remaining as a [[Chapel of Ease|chapel-of-ease]]. Old St Peter's was demolished in 1974, while St Nicholas' Church has been converted into the diocesan offices but remains consecrated. Continued expansion south has led to the creation of an additional more recent parish of St Justus (1956) covering The Tideway [[housing estate|estate]] and surrounding area.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rochester.anglican.org/churches/rad/rochester/rochester/parish-details.htm#st_margaret/index.htm |title=Rochester Diocese |publisher=Rochester.anglican.org |accessdate=2 September 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926204818/http://www.rochester.anglican.org/churches/rad/rochester/rochester/parish-details.htm#st_margaret/index.htm#st_margaret/index.htm |archive-date=26 September 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nA church dedicated to St Mary the Virgin at [[City gate|Eastgate]], which was of Anglo-Saxon foundation, is understood to have constituted a parish until the Middle Ages, but few records survive.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rbt.org.uk/news/2012/newsitem17.htm|title=www.rbt.org.uk|access-date=5 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924084945/http://www.rbt.org.uk/news/2012/newsitem17.htm|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Governance==\nOn 1 April 1974, the City Council was abolished under the [[Local Government Act 1972]], and the territory was merged with the [[District of Medway]], [[Chatham, Kent|Borough of Chatham]] and most of [[Strood Rural District]], including the parishes of [[Cuxton]], [[Halling, Kent|Halling]] and [[Cliffe-at-Hoo|Cliffe]], and the [[Hoo Peninsula]], to form a new a [[local government district]] called the [[Borough of Medway]], within the county of Kent. [[Medway Borough Council]] applied to inherit Rochester's city status, but this was refused; instead [[letters patent]] were granted constituting the area of the former Rochester local government district to be the City of Rochester, to \"perpetuate the ancient name\" and to recall \"the long history and proud heritage of the said City\".<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=46243|page=3651|date=21 March 1974}} Letters Patent dated 18 March 1974, text also available from [http://cityark.medway.gov.uk/ Medway Council archives website]</ref> The [[Home Office]] said that the city status may be extended to the entire borough if it had \"Rochester\" in its name, so in 1979, Medway Borough Council renamed the borough to [[Borough of Rochester-upon-Medway]], and in 1982, Rochester's city status was transferred to the entire borough by letters patent, with the district being called the [[City of Rochester-upon-Medway]].<ref name=\"LondonGazette48875\"/> The [[Admiral]] of the River Medway was ''ex-officio'' Mayor of Rochester and this dignity transferred to the Mayor of Medway when that unitary authority was created, along with the Admiralty Court for the River which constitutes a committee of the Council.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medway.gov.uk/thecouncilanddemocracy/mayor/civicfunctions.aspx|title=www.medway.gov.uk|access-date=21 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141221173032/http://www.medway.gov.uk/thecouncilanddemocracy/mayor/civicfunctions.aspx|archive-date=21 December 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n[[File:GuildhallRochester.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.9|<center>[[Rochester Guildhall|The Guildhall]], Rochester</center>]]\n\nOn 1 April 1998, the existing local government districts of Rochester-upon-Medway and [[Gillingham, Kent|Gillingham]] were abolished and became the new [[unitary authority]] of [[Medway]]. The [[Department of Environment, Transport and the Regions]] informed the city council that since it was the [[local government district]] that officially held City status under the 1982 Letters Patent, the council would need to appoint [[charter trustees]] to preserve its city status, but the outgoing [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]-run council decided not to appoint \"[[Charter Trustees]]\", so the city status was lost when Rochester-upon-Medway was abolished as a local government district.<ref name=\"Error costs Rochester city status\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/1991827.stm |title=Error costs Rochester city status |work=BBC News |date=16 May 2002 |accessdate=2 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/kent/7511023.stm |title=Town seeks to regain city status |work=BBC News |date=17 July 2008 |accessdate=2 September 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"EasternDaily\">{{cite news|url=http://www.edp24.co.uk/news/medway_city_bid_aims_to_bring_city_status_back_to_the_area_1_924248|date=1 June 2011|publisher=[[Archant Community Media]]|newspaper=[[Eastern Daily Press]]|accessdate=11 April 2015|url-status=dead|archivedate=11 April 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150411143415/http://www.edp24.co.uk/news/medway_city_bid_aims_to_bring_city_status_back_to_the_area_1_924248|title=Medway City bid aims to bring city status back to the area|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Bowen2003\">{{cite report|first=Mark|url=http://democracy.medway.gov.uk/data/regeneration%20&%20community%20overview%20and%20scrutiny%20committee/20030304/agenda/report%20(agenda%20item%205)%203.pdf|url-status=live|accessdate=11 April 2015|archivedate=27 October 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141027004924/http://democracy.medway.gov.uk/Data/Regeneration%20%26%20Community%20Overview%20and%20Scrutiny%20Committee/20030304/Agenda/Report%20%28Agenda%20item%205%29%203.pdf|date=4 March 2004|title=Rochester City Status|publisher=[[Medway Council]]|last=Bowen|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Hicks2010\">{{cite report|last=Hicks|first=Richard|url=http://democracy.medway.gov.uk/mgconvert2pdf.aspx?id=6327|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150411144234/http://democracy.medway.gov.uk/mgconvert2pdf.aspx?id=6327|accessdate=11 April 2015|archivedate=11 April 2015|url-status=live|title=City Status Report|publisher=Medway Council|date=25 November 2010}}</ref> The other local government districts with City status that were abolished around this time, [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]] and [[Hereford]], decided to appoint [[Charter Trustees]] to maintain the existence of their own cities and the mayoralties. The incoming Medway Council apparently only became aware of this when, in 2002, it was advised that Rochester was not on the [[Lord Chancellor's Office]]'s list of cities.<ref>[http://democracy.medway.gov.uk/Data/Regeneration%20&%20Community%20Overview%20and%20Scrutiny%20Committee/20030304/Agenda/Report%20(Agenda%20item%205)%203.pdf Medway Council \u2013 Regeneration and Community Overview and Scrutiny Committee, Report on Rochester City Status], 4 March 2003.</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Medway Council started to refer to the \"City of Medway\" in promotional material, but it was rebuked and instructed not to do so in future by the [[Advertising Standards Authority (United Kingdom)|Advertising Standards Authority]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.asa.org.uk/Rulings/Adjudications/2011/3/Medway-Council/TF_ADJ_49924.aspx |title= Adjudication on Medway Council |publisher= Advertising Standards Authority |date=16 March 2011 |accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> Subsequently, the Medway Unitary Authority has applied for City status for Medway as a whole, rather than merely for Rochester. Medway applied unsuccessfully for City status in 2000 and 2002 and again in the Queen's Diamond Jubilee Year of 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/kent/8585429.stm |title=Medway Council in Kent makes bid for 2012 city status |work=BBC News |date=24 March 2010 |accessdate=2 September 2011}}</ref> Any future bid to regain formal City status has been recommended to be made under the aegis of '''''Rochester-upon-Medway'''''.\n\nThe 2011 definition of Rochester includes [[Strood]] to the northwest and is defined as an urban subdivision with a 2011 population of 62,982.<ref name=\"nomisweb.co.uk\"/>\n\n[[Kelly Tolhurst]] [[Member of parliament|MP]] is the current parliamentary representative for [[Rochester and Strood (UK Parliament constituency)|the constituency]].\n\n==Geography==\n{{Further|Geography of Kent}}\nRochester lies within the area, known to [[geologist]]s, as the [[London Basin]]. The low-lying [[Hoo peninsula]] to the north of the town consists of [[London Clay]], and the [[alluvium]] brought down by the two rivers\u2014the [[River Thames|Thames]] and the [[River Medway|Medway]]\u2014whose confluence is in this area. The land rises from the river, and being on the dip slope of the [[North Downs]], this consists of [[chalk]] surmounted by the Blackheath Beds of sand and gravel.\n\nAs a [[human settlement]], Rochester became established as the lowest river crossing of the River Medway, well before the arrival of the Romans.\n\nIt is a focal point between two routes, being part of the main route connecting London with the Continent and the north-south routes following the course of the Medway connecting [[Maidstone]] and the [[Weald of Kent]] with the Thames and the North Sea. The Thames Marshes were an important source of [[Sea salt|salt]]. Rochester's roads follow north Kent's valleys and ridges of steep-sided [[chalk]] [[bourne (stream)|bournes]]. There are four ways out of town to the south: up Star Hill, via [[Dairy|The Delce]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/survey-kent/vol4/pp153-182|title=The city and liberty of Rochester: The city parishes - British History Online|website=www.british-history.ac.uk}}</ref> along the Maidstone Road or through [[Borstal, Kent|Borstal]]. The town is inextricably linked with the neighbouring [[Medway Towns]] but separated from [[Maidstone]] by a protective [[ridge]] known as the [[North Downs|Downs]], a designated [[area of Outstanding Natural Beauty]].\n\nAt its most limited geographical size, Rochester is defined as the market town within the [[city wall]]s, now associated with the historic medieval city. However, Rochester historically also included the ancient [[Ward (electoral subdivision)|wards]] of Strood Intra on the river's west bank, and Chatham Intra as well as the three old [[Parish (Church of England)|parishes]] on the Medway's east bank.\n\nThe [[diocese of Rochester]] is another geographical entity which can be referred to as Rochester.\n<!-- Within the city boundaries are several distinct areas: the town centre near the parish church and along the High Street; The Delce area; Strood estate constructed in 1927;\n\n{{Geographic location\n|title ='''Neighbouring areas of Rochester'''\n|Northwest = [[Strood]]\n|North = ''[[Hoo Peninsula]]''\n|Northeast = [[Chatham]]\n|West = [[Gravesend]]\n|Centre = Rochester\n|East = [[Gillingham, Kent]]\n|Southwest = [[Cuxton]] and [[Halling]]\n|South = [[Rochester Airport]] and [[Maidstone]]\n|Southeast = [[Walderslade, Kent]]\n}}\n\nOther nearby localities:\n*[[Chattenden]]\n*[[Cliffe]]\n*[[Cobham Park]]\n*[[Cooling]]\n*[[Hoo St Werbergh]]\n*[[Rainham, Kent]]\n-->\n\n==Climate==\nRochester has an [[oceanic climate]] similar to much of southern England, being accorded [[K\u00f6ppen Climate Classification|K\u00f6ppen Climate Classification-subtype]] of \"[[Oceanic climate|Cfb]]\" (Marine West Coast Climate).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather-summary.php3?s=68730&cityname=Gravesend,+England,+United+Kingdom&units=|title=Gravesend, England K\u00f6ppen Climate Classification (Weatherbase)|website=Weatherbase}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 August 2003, neighbouring [[Gravesend]] recorded one of the highest temperatures since meteorogical records began in the [[United Kingdom]], with a reading of 38.1 degrees Celsius (100.6 degrees Fahrenheit),<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/august/10/newsid_3910000/3910801.stm 2003: Britain swelters in record heat]. http://www.bbc.co.uk 10 August 2003. Retrieved on 28 January 2012.</ref> only beaten by [[Brogdale]], near [[Faversham]], {{convert|22|mi|km|0}} to the ESE.<ref>[http://www.metoffice.com/climate/uk/2003/ 2003 weather summaries] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030220163131/http://www.metoffice.com/climate/uk/2003/ |date=20 February 2003 }}. Met Office. Retrieved on 28 January 2012.</ref> The weather station at Brogdale is run by a volunteer, only reporting its data once a month, whereas [[Gravesend]], which has an official Met Office site at the PLA pilot station,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/public/weather/forecast/u10k8kx5v|title=Gravesend weather forecast|website=Met Office}}</ref> reports data hourly.\n\nBeing near the mouth of the Thames Estuary with the North Sea, Rochester is relatively close to [[continental Europe]] and enjoys a somewhat less temperate climate than other parts of Kent and most of East Anglia. It is therefore less cloudy, drier and less prone to [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]] [[Low-pressure area|depressions]] with their associated wind and rain than western regions of Britain, as well as being hotter in summer and colder in winter. Rochester city centre's micro-climate is more accurately reflected by these officially recorded figures than by readings taken at Rochester Airport.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rochester-airport.co.uk/|title=www.rochester-airport.co.uk|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nNorth and [[North West Kent]] continue to record higher temperatures in [[summer]], sometimes being the hottest area of the country, ''eg.'' on the warmest day of 2011, when temperatures reached 33.1 degrees.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-13936256 | work=BBC News | title=Flash flood warnings for parts of England | date=27 June 2011}}</ref> Additionally, it holds at least two records for the year 2010, of 30.9 degrees<ref>[http://news.uk.msn.com/uk/articles.aspx?cp-documentid=153946459&ocid=today 27 June 2010 Britain basks, but showers due] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131226192412/http://news.uk.msn.com/uk/articles.aspx?cp-documentid=153946459&ocid=today |date=26 December 2013 }}. http://www.news.uk.msn.com {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140928104406/http://news.uk.msn.com/ |date=28 September 2014 }} (28 June 2010). Retrieved on 28 January 2012.</ref> and 31.7 degrees C.<ref>Attewill, Fred. (14 October 2011) [http://www.metro.co.uk/news/834794-weekend-hot-weather-saw-brits-flocking-to-the-beaches Weekend hot weather saw Brits flocking to the beaches]. Metro.co.uk. Retrieved on 28 January 2012.</ref> Another record was set during England's Indian summer of 2011 with 29.9 degrees C., the highest temperature ever recorded in the UK for October.\n\n{{Weather box|location = Stanford-le-Hope (nearest climate station to Gravesend) 1981\u20132010\n|metric first = Yes\n|single line = Yes\n|Jan high C = 7.9\n|Feb high C = 8.0\n|Mar high C = 10.9\n|Apr high C = 13.2\n|May high C = 16.8\n|Jun high C = 19.9\n|Jul high C = 22.1\n|Aug high C = 22.2\n|Sep high C = 19.4\n|Oct high C = 15.2\n|Nov high C = 10.8\n|Dec high C = 8.1\n|year high C = \n|Jan low C = 2.2\n|Feb low C = 1.6\n|Mar low C = 3.3\n|Apr low C = 4.7\n|May low C = 7.5\n|Jun low C = 10.5\n|Jul low C = 13.0\n|Aug low C = 12.5\n|Sep low C = 10.3\n|Oct low C = 7.4\n|Nov low C = 4.4\n|Dec low C = 2.4\n|year low C = \n|Jan precipitation mm = 47.9\n|Feb precipitation mm = 36.7\n|Mar precipitation mm = 37.6\n|Apr precipitation mm = 40.9\n|May precipitation mm = 48.0\n|Jun precipitation mm = 41.1\n|Jul precipitation mm = 52.5\n|Aug precipitation mm = 44.8\n|Sep precipitation mm = 45.5\n|Oct precipitation mm = 64.9\n|Nov precipitation mm = 57.8\n|Dec precipitation mm = 53.8\n|year precipitation mm = \n|Jan sun = 60.0\n|Feb sun = 77.7\n|Mar sun = 113.4\n|Apr sun = 161.5\n|May sun = 194.3\n|Jun sun = 198.7\n|Jul sun = 208.7\n|Aug sun = 195.5\n|Sep sun = 151.1\n|Oct sun = 117.9\n|Nov sun = 74.0\n|Dec sun = 48.6\n|year sun = \n|source 1 = [[Met Office]]}}\n\n==Buildings==\n\nRochester comprises numerous important historic buildings, the most prominent of which are the [[Guildhall]], the [[Corn Exchange]], [[Restoration House]], Eastgate House, as well as [[Rochester Castle]] and [[Rochester Cathedral]]. Many of the town centre's old buildings date from as early as the 14th century up to the 18th century.  The [[chapel]] of [[St. Bartholomew's Hospital, Rochester|St Bartholomew's Hospital]] dates from the ancient priory hospital's foundation in 1078.\n\n==Economy==\n{{See also|Chatham Dockyard}}\n[[File:Rochester2007Dickens0650c.JPG|thumb|<center>'''Rochester High Street'''</center>]]\nThomas Aveling started a small business in 1850 producing and repairing [[List of agricultural machinery|agricultural plant equipment]].  In 1861 this became the firm of [[Aveling and Porter]], which was to become the largest manufacturer of agricultural machinery and [[steamroller|steam roller]]s in the country.<ref name=Shire>*Discovering Traction Engines, \u2013 Harold Bonnett \u2013 Shire Publications (1975) \u2013 {{ISBN|0-85263-318-1}}</ref> Aveling was elected Admiral of the River Medway (i.e. Mayor of Rochester) for 1869-70.\n\n==Culture==\n\n===Sweeps Festival===\nSince 1980 the city has seen the revival of the historic Rochester [[Jack-in-the-Green]] [[May Day]] dancing [[chimney sweeps]] tradition, which had died out in the early 1900s. Though not unique to Rochester (similar sweeps' gatherings were held across southern England, notably in Bristol, Deptford, Whitstable and Hastings), its revival was directly inspired by Dickens' description of the celebration in [[Sketches by Boz]].\n\nThe festival has since grown from a small gathering of local [[Morris dance]] sides to one of the largest in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visitkent.co.uk/events/9580/|title=Search for events, activities and exhibitions across Kent|access-date=21 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141221165116/http://www.visitkent.co.uk/events/9580/|archive-date=21 December 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The festival begins with the \"Awakening of Jack-in-the-Green\" ceremony,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/medway/news/thousands-turn-out-for-sweeps-16739/|title=Thousands turn out for Sweeps Festival|publisher=}}</ref> and continues in Rochester High Street over the May [[Bank Holiday]] weekend.\n\nThere are numerous other festivals in Rochester apart from the Sweeps Festival. The association with Dickens is the theme for Rochester's two Dickens Festivals held annually in June and December.<ref name=\"historic-uk1\">{{cite web|author=Historic uk \u2013 heritage of britain accommodation guide |url= http://www.historic-uk.com/DestinationsUK/Rochester.htm |title=Destinations UK \u2013 Rochester, Kent, England |publisher=Historic UK |date=6 June 2010 |accessdate=1 September 2010}}</ref> [[The Medway Fuse Festival]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fusefestival.org.uk/|title=Fuse Festival \u2013 Come party with us|website=fusefestival.org.uk}}</ref> usually arranges performances in Rochester and the latest festival to take shape is the Rochester Literature Festival, the brainchild of three local writers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rochesterlitfest.com/|title=Rochester Literature Festival|website=Rochester Literature Festival}}</ref>\n\n===Library===\nA new [[public library]] was built alongside the Adult Education Centre, Eastgate. This enabled the registry office to move from Maidstone Road, Chatham into the Corn Exchange on Rochester High Street (where the library was formerly housed). As mentioned in a report presented to Medway Council's ''Community Services Overview and Scrutiny Committee'' on 28 March 2006, the new library opened in late summer (2006).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visitmedway.org/places-of-interest/rochester-library|title=www.visitmedway.org|access-date=21 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141221174118/http://www.visitmedway.org/places-of-interest/rochester-library|archive-date=21 December 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Huguenot Museum===\nA new Huguenot Museum, which includes items from the collections of the [[French Hospital (La Providence)|French Hospital]], was opened in Rochester on 13 May 2015, with support from the Heritage Lottery Fund and individual donations.<ref>Website of the [http://www.huguenotmuseum.org/ Huguenot Museum], Rochester, Kent, located not far from the French Hospital itself.</ref>\n\n===Theatre===\n[[File:2006SweepsSideRochester.JPG|thumb|Sweeps festival in 2006]]\nThere is a small amateur theatre called Medway Little Theatre on St Margaret's Banks next to Rochester High Street opposite the former railway station.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.danwillis.freeserve.co.uk/ |title= Medway Little Theatre |access-date= 31 January 2012 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120416041818/http://www.danwillis.freeserve.co.uk/ |archive-date= 16 April 2012 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref> The theatre was formed out of a creative alliance with the Medway Theatre Club, managed by Marion Martin, at St Luke's Methodist Church on City Way, Rochester<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medwaymethodistchurch.org.uk/stlukesmethodistchurchce.htm|title=St Luke's - Gillingham Methodist Church - NKMC|website=www.medwaymethodistchurch.org.uk|access-date=28 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141228232049/http://www.medwaymethodistchurch.org.uk/stlukesmethodistchurchce.htm|archive-date=28 December 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> between 1985 and 1988, since when drama and theatre studies have become well established in Rochester owing to the dedication of the Medway Theatre Club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.danwillis.freeserve.co.uk/stoppress.htm|title=''Medway Theatre Club''|access-date=28 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141222213208/http://www.danwillis.freeserve.co.uk/stoppress.htm|archive-date=22 December 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Media===\nLocal newspapers for Rochester include the ''Medway Messenger'', published by the [[KM Group]], and free papers.\n\nThe local commercial [[Radio broadcasting|radio station]] for Rochester is [[KMFM Medway]], owned by the KM Group. Medway is also served by community radio station [[Radio Sunlight]] which is now an online service. The area also receives broadcasts from county-wide stations [[BBC Radio Kent]], [[Heart Kent|Heart]] and [[Gold (radio)|Gold]], as well as from various [[Essex]] and [[Greater London]] radio stations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radio-now.co.uk/south.htm#KENT|title=radio-now.co.uk - Kent, Surrey and Sussex radio stations|first=|last=radionow|website=www.radio-now.co.uk}}</ref>\nRochester is part of the [[ITV Meridian]] and [[BBC South East]] area, receiving television signals from the [[Bluebell Hill]] transmitter on the crest of the [[North Downs]] to the SE, supplemented by a low power relay transmitter in central Chatham.\n\n===Sport===\n[[association football|Football]] is played with many teams competing in Saturday and Sunday leagues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leaguewebsite.co.uk/randd/Home|title=Rochester and District Football League - Home Page|website=www.leaguewebsite.co.uk}}</ref> The local football club is [[Rochester United F.C.|Rochester United F.C]]. Rochester F.C. was its old football club but has been defunct for many decades. [[Rugby football|Rugby]] is also played; Medway R.F.C. play their matches at Priestfields and ''Old Williamsonians'' is associated with [[Sir Joseph Williamson's Mathematical School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oldwilliamsonianclub.com/|title=oldwilliamsonianclub.com \u2013 oldwilliamsonianclub.com|website=www.oldwilliamsonianclub.com}}</ref>\n\n[[Cricket]] is played in the town, with teams entered in the [[Kent Cricket League]].\n[[Holcombe Hockey Club]] enter teams in both the [[Men's England Hockey League|Men's]] and [[Women's England Hockey League]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.holcombehc.org.uk/|title=Holcombe Hockey Club|website=www.holcombehc.org.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.englandhockey.co.uk/fl/ehl/tables.asp?section=355/|title=EHL league tables|accessdate=18 March 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141221171444/http://www.englandhockey.co.uk/fl/ehl/tables.asp?section=355%2F|archivedate=21 December 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Motorcycle speedway|Speedway]] was staged on a track adjacent to City Way that opened in 1932. Proposals for a revival in the early 1970s did not materialise and the ''Rochester Bombers'' became the [[Romford Bombers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.national-speedway-museum.co.uk/romform%20speedway%20track.html|title=www.national-speedway-museum.co.uk|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nSailing and rowing are also popular on the River Medway with respective clubs being based in Rochester.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medwayyachtclub.com/|title=Medway Yacht Club|website=Medway Yacht Club}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medwaytownsrowingclub.co.uk/|title=medway-rowing|website=medway-rowing}}</ref>\n\n===Film===\nThe 1959 [[James Bond]] ''[[Goldfinger (novel)|Goldfinger]]'' describes Bond driving along the [[A2 road (Great Britain)|A2]] through the Medway Towns from Strood to Chatham. Of interest is the mention of \"inevitable traffic jams\" on the [[Strood]] side of [[Rochester Bridge]], the novel being written some years prior to the construction of the [[M2 motorway (Great Britain)|M2 motorway]] Medway bypass.\n\nRochester is the setting of the controversial 1965 [[Peter Watkins]] television film ''[[The War Game]]'', which depicts the town's destruction by a nuclear missile.<ref name=WarGame>{{cite web|url=http://www.museum.tv/archives/etv/W/htmlW/wargamethe/wargamethe.htm |title=War Game, The |publisher=Museum.tv |date=31 July 1985 |accessdate=1 September 2010}}</ref> The opening sequence was shot in Chatham Town Hall, but the credits particularly thank the people of [[Dover]], [[Gravesend]] and [[Tonbridge]].\n\nThe 2011 adventure film ''[[Ironclad (film)|Ironclad]]'' is based upon the [[First Barons' War#Sieges of Windsor and Rochester|1215 siege of Rochester Castle]]. There are however [[Ironclad (film)#Fictional elements|areas where the plot differs from accepted historical narrative]].\n\n===Notable people===\n[[File:Rochester High Street looking east.jpg|right|thumb|Rochester High Street]]\n;Charles Dickens:\nThe historic city was for many years the favourite of [[Charles Dickens]], who lived within the diocese at nearby [[Gads Hill Place]], [[Higham, Kent|Higham]], many of his novels being based on the area. Descriptions of the town appear in ''[[Pickwick Papers]]'', ''[[Great Expectations]]'' and (lightly fictionalised as \"Cloisterham\") in ''[[The Mystery of Edwin Drood]]''. Elements of two houses in Rochester, Satis House and [[Restoration House]], are used for [[Miss Havisham]]'s house in ''Great Expectations'', [[Satis House]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OlWQNGB5628C&pg=PA97&lpg=PA97&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Follow These Writers|author= Judith Bastide|page=97|publisher=Author House|date= 1 April 2013}}</ref>\n;Dame Sybil Thorndike and Russell Thorndike:\nThe actress Dame [[Sybil Thorndike]] and her brother [[Russell Thorndike|Russell]] were brought up in Minor Canon Row adjacent to the cathedral; the daughter of a [[Canon (priest)|canon]] of Rochester Cathedral, she was educated at [[Rochester Grammar School for Girls]].  A local doctors' practice,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.thorndike.nhs.uk|title=Dame Sybil Thorndike Practice |accessdate=30 October 2011}}</ref> local dental practice<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.thorndent.co.uk|title=Thorndike Dental Practice |accessdate=30 October 2011}}</ref> and a hall at Rochester Grammar School are all named after her.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thelondonquartet.blogspot.co.uk/2011/06/thorndike-arts-centre-rochester.html|title=Thorndike Arts Centre, Rochester|website=thelondonquartet.blogspot.co.uk}}</ref>\n;Sir Peter Buck:\n[[Peter Buck (mayor)|Sir Peter Buck]] was [[Mayor of Medway|Admiral of the Medway]] in the 17th century; [[knight]]ed in 1603 he and [[William Barlow (bishop of Lincoln)|Bishop Barlow]] hosted [[James VI and I|King James]], the [[House of Stuart|Stuart royal family]] and the [[Christian IV of Denmark|King of Denmark]] in 1606. A [[Honourable Corps of Gentlemen at Arms|civil servant]] to [[Chatham Dockyard|The Royal Dockyard]] and [[Lord High Admiral of the United Kingdom|Lord High Admiral]], Buck lived at [[Eastgate House, Rochester]].\n;Denis Redman:\nMajor-General [[Denis Redman]], a [[World War II]] veteran, was born and raised in Rochester and later became a founder member of [[REME]], head of his Corps and a [[Major-general (United Kingdom)|Major-General in the British Army]].\n;Kelly Brook\nThe [[Model (people)|model]] and actress [[Kelly Brook]] went to Delce Junior School in Rochester and later the [[The Thomas Aveling School|Thomas Aveling School]] (formerly Warren Wood Girls School).\n\n==Education==\n\n{{for|a full list of schools serving Rochester|List of schools in Medway}}\nMedway council run a [[Selective school#United Kingdom|selective system of education]], similar to other local authorities in Kent, but call their [[secondary modern school]]s ''secondary schools''. Almost all secondary schools in Rochester have opted for [[Academy (English school)|academy]] status.\n\nIn 1701, [[Sir Joseph Williamson]] left a bequest to establish the [[Sir Joseph Williamson's Mathematical School|Mathematical School]], a boys' grammar school, also referred to either as ''Rochester Math'' or ''The Math School''.  Unlike earlier educational foundations, such as [[King's School, Rochester|The King's School]], it was not tied to a religious establishment, but was opened for practical instruction of boys in navigation and mathematics.\n\nThe [[University for the Creative Arts]], formerly the Kent Institute of Art & Design, is located on the boundary of Rochester with Chatham.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucreative.ac.uk/rochester|title=University for the Creative Arts - UCA Rochester - UCA|website=University for the Creative Arts}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\n[[File:rochesterrear.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.05|The old [[Rochester railway station|Rochester Station]] (overground): <br>the rail tracks run along a [[viaduct]].]]\n;Road\nRochester is on the [[A2 road (Great Britain)|A2]], which crosses the Medway at [[Rochester Bridge]] \u2013 the route roughly follows the [[ancient trackway|ancient road]] known as [[Watling Street]], first paved by the Romans, but used by earlier Britons for centuries before the Roman invasion. Nowadays vehicular traffic is largely diverted onto the nearby [[M2 motorway (Great Britain)|M2 motorway]].\n[[Watling Street]] passes through the town, and slightly to the south both the [[M2 motorway (Great Britain)|M2 motorway]] and the [[High Speed 1]] railway line bridge the [[River Medway]].\n;Bus\nBus services are operated by [[Arriva Southern Counties]], which took over the locally owned [[Maidstone & District Motor Services|Maidstone & District]] bus company in the 1990s. Other local bus companies including [[Nu-Venture]] provide certain services, some contracted from the local council.\n;Rail\n{{Medway area RDT}}\n[[Rochester railway station]] is on the [[Chatham Main Line]] and the [[North Kent Line]]. [[Strood railway station]] is on the North Kent Line and the [[Medway Valley Line]]; it links to the HS1 high speed line at [[Ebbsfleet International]] giving a running time of 30 minutes into [[St Pancras railway station|St Pancras]]. All services are provided by [[Southeastern (train operating company)|Southeastern]].\n;Air\n[[Rochester Airport, England|Rochester Airport]] began in September 1933 when Rochester City Council purchased some land as the site for a municipal [[airport]]. One month later the aircraft manufacturers [[Short Brothers]] leased the land for test flying. By 1934\u20135 Short Brothers had taken over the site, and moved in some of their personnel from the existing [[seaplane]] works. The inaugural flight into Rochester was from [[Gravesend, Kent|Gravesend]], John Parker flying the Short Brothers [[Short Scion]] G-ACJI.\n\nIn 1979 the lease reverted to the City Council. After giving thorough consideration to closing the airport, [[General Electric Company plc|GEC]] (then comprising [[Marconi Company|Marconi]] and instrument makers [[Elliott Brothers (computer company)|Elliot Automation]]) decided to take over management of the airport. It maintained two grass [[runway|landing strip]]s while releasing some land for light industrial expansion.\n\n==Further reading==\n* R, Marsh, 1976, The Evolution of a City (Medway Borough)\n* F.F. Smith, 1976, A History of Rochester (JHP Reprint) 9780905540009\n\n==See also==\n*[[Rainham, Kent|Rainham]]\n*[[HM Prison Rochester]]\n*[[Rochester and Strood (UK Parliament constituency)]]\n*[[Earl of Rochester]]\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Rochester, Kent}}\n* [http://www.medway.gov.uk Medway Council Official Site]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100329110819/http://www.medway.gov.uk/medwayimages/ Archive Images]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20000816190442/http://www.rochesterairport.flyer.co.uk/ Rochester Airport and British Aviation]\n* [http://www.glentour.freeuk.com/rochester_sweeps_festival.htm Photographs of the Rochester Sweeps Festival]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071024110949/http://video.google.com/videoplay?docid=6380511021213931299 Google video of Morris Dancers] at Sweeps Festival Rochester 1997\n* [http://rochesterlitfest.com/ Rochester Literature Festival]\n* [http://www.rochestercathedral.org/ www.rochestercathedral.org]\n\n{{Medway}}\n{{Kent}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rochester, Kent| ]]\n[[Category:Medway]]\n[[Category:Market towns in Kent]]\n[[Category:Towns in Kent]]\n[[Category:Towns with cathedrals in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "82.31.115.179", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eCivic history and traditions)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rochester,_Kent"}
{"title_page": "Mae Shumway Enderly", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Mae Shumway Enderly\n| image              = MaeShumwayEnderly1916.png\n| alt                = Mae Shumway Enderly, dressed in a Norwegian bridal costume, from a 1916 publication.\n| caption            = Mae Shumway Enderly, dressed in a Norwegian bridal costume from a 1916 publication.\n| birth_name         = Minnie Mae Shumway\n| birth_date         = October 30, 1871\n| birth_place        = Galesburg, Illinois\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = American\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = harpist, entertainer\n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = lyceum circuit, Chautauquas, vaudeville\n| notable_works      = \n}}\n\n'''Mae Shumway Enderly''' (October 30, 1871 \u2013 after May 1943<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/31425361/mae_shumway_enderly_1943/|title=Internationalists Plan Luncheon|last=|first=|date=June 13, 1943|work=The Los Angeles Times|access-date=May 10, 2019|page=63|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>) was an American clubwoman, harpist and entertainer on the lyceum platform, the [[Chautauqua]] circuit, and the [[vaudeville]] stage.\n\n== Early life ==\nMinnie Mae Shumway was born in [[Galesburg, Illinois]], the daughter of Stephen Burroughs Shumway and Lydia Jane Streeter Shumway.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/historyofwestern03shum|quote=Mae Shumway Enderly.|title=History of Western Nebraska and Its People: General History. Cheyenne, Box Butte, Deuel, Garden, Sioux, Kimball, Morrill, Sheridan, Scotts Bluff, Banner, and Dawes Counties. A Group Often Called the Panhandle of Nebraska|last=Shumway|first=Grant Lee|date=1921|publisher=Western Publishing & Engraving Company|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/historyofwestern03shum/page/418 418]-419|language=en}}</ref> She pursued training for the stage at the Frohman School for Expression in New York.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=May 1923|title=Mae Shumway Enderly is from Noted Early Family|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-mflAAAAMAAJ&lpg=RA7-PA35&ots=XhXEfUerwm&dq=Mae%20Shumway%20Enderly&pg=RA11-PA33#v=onepage&q=Mae%20Shumway%20Enderly&f=false|journal=Lyceum Magazine|volume=32|pages=33|via=}}</ref>\n \n== Career ==\nMae Shumway moved to Nebraska with her family as a young woman, and taught school there.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n[https://healthcare2410.blogspot.com/2020/03/Corona-virus-covid-19.html?m=1 Corona virus:- \u0915\u094b\u0930\u094b\u0928\u093e \u0935\u093e\u092f\u0930\u0938 \u0932\u0915\u094d\u0937\u0923, \u092a\u0939\u091a\u093e\u0928, \u092c\u091a\u093e\u0935] \n\nMae Shumway Enderly's performances for the lyceum, Chautauqua, and vaudeville audiences involved various costumes, singing, impersonating historical and cultural figures or giving dramatic readings, sometimes while also playing a small [[Celtic harp|Irish harp]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/31424792/mae_shumway_enderly_1926/|title=Harpologist Ends Tour|last=|first=|date=December 26, 1926|work=The Los Angeles Times|access-date=May 10, 2019|page=64|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>  \"I have spent weeks searching in the public libraries of Los Angeles and other cities,\" she explained about her material, \"I am continually searching the best magazines and periodicals for authentic news so that I may improve my programs.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nEnderly was popular with American audiences.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/31407474/mae_shumway_enderly_1925/|title=Mae Enderly Returns|last=|first=|date=May 24, 1925|work=The Los Angeles Times|access-date=May 9, 2019|page=68|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> In 1909 she toured with soprano Gloria Mayne-Windsor, as the Enderly-Windsor Company.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/31406547/mae_shumway_enderly_1909/|title=Enderly-Windsor Company Charms Audience|last=|first=|date=October 12, 1909|work=Albuquerque Journal|access-date=May 9, 2019|page=4|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>  For several years (at least 1909-1914) she gave a costumed dramatic reading called \"The Spanish Student\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/entertainment-clipping-nov-18-1910-1174146/|title='The Spanish Student' for High School This Evening|last=|first=|date=November 18, 1910|work=Oxnard Daily Courier|access-date=May 9, 2019|page=1|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/?a=d&d=CC19140428.2.14&srpos=1&e=-------en--20--1--txt-txIN-Mae+Shumway-------1|title=High Class Concert|last=|first=|date=April 28, 1914|work=Calexico Chronicle|access-date=May 9, 2019|page=1|via=California Digital Newspaper Collection}}</ref> During [[World War I]] she developed a sketch called \"Brides of Our Allies\" or \"Peasant Brides\",<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/31406863/mae_shumway_enderly_1916/|title=May Shumway Enderly Wearing Costume of a Norwegian Bride|last=|first=|date=July 3, 1916|work=Neenah Daily Times|access-date=May 9, 2019|page=3|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> in which she wore wedding gowns from various European cultures,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/31424698/mae_shumway_enderly_1926/|title=Women Entertained by Bridal Costumes|last=|first=|date=May 28, 1926|work=The Van Nuys News|access-date=May 10, 2019|page=1|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> and discussed those traditions while she sang and played the harp.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://digital.lib.uiowa.edu/cdm/ref/collection/tc/id/37576|title=Mae Shumway Enderly :: Traveling Culture - Circuit Chautauqua in the Twentieth Century|website=digital.lib.uiowa.edu|access-date=2019-05-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=January 1923|title=Praises Costume Program|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-mflAAAAMAAJ&lpg=RA7-PA35&ots=XhXEfUerwm&dq=Mae%20Shumway%20Enderly&pg=RA7-PA35#v=onepage&q=Mae%20Shumway%20Enderly&f=false|journal=Lyceum Magazine|volume=32|pages=35|via=}}</ref> She presented a \"tragic playlet\" called \"Ballard of Despair\" to Los Angeles club audiences in 1917.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/?a=d&d=RDP19170402.2.58&srpos=6&e=-------en--20--1--txt-txIN-Mae+Shumway-------1|title=Well Known Reader to Present Tragic Playlet|last=|first=|date=April 2, 1917|work=Riverside Daily Press|access-date=May 9, 2019|page=1|via=California Digital Newspaper Collection}}</ref> She sang Irish songs and played harp in costume at the [[Ebell Society|Ebell Club]] in Los Angeles for [[Saint Patrick's Day|St. Patrick's Day]] in 1919.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/?a=d&d=LAH19190318.2.83&srpos=5&e=-------en--20--1--txt-txIN-Mae+Shumway-------1|title=Boy Baritone Feature of St. Patrick's Day Fete|last=|first=|date=March 18, 1919|work=Los Angeles Herald|access-date=May 9, 2019|page=13|via=California Digital Newspaper Collection}}</ref> She recited \"[[Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam|The Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam]]\" while wearing a \"Persian costume\" at the harp, or poems by Edgar Guest, with harp accompaniment she wrote.<ref name=\":1\" />  \n\nEnderly also played harp and gave her spoken presentations for radio audiences. As a prominent clubwoman, she was the official head hostess to Illinois attendees during the [[1932 Summer Olympics]] in Los Angeles.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/31425017/mae_shumway_enderly_1932/|title=Knox College Alumni to be Entertained|last=|first=|date=July 31, 1932|work=The Los Angeles Times|access-date=May 10, 2019|page=38|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/31425121/mae_shumway_engerly_1932/|title=Olympic Activity|last=|first=|date=July 1, 1932|work=The Los Angeles Times|access-date=May 10, 2019|page=26|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> In 1933 she was founder and president of the International Woman's Club of Los Angeles (formerly known as the Illinois-California Women's Breakfast Club).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/31407357/mae_shumway_enderly_1933/|title=Presidents Start to Make Plans for Next Club Year|last=|first=|date=August 13, 1933|work=The Los Angeles Times|access-date=May 9, 2019|page=32|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/31424326/mae_shumway_enderly_1933/|title=International Club Plays Host to Indian Group at Colorful Meeting|last=|first=|date=August 30, 1933|work=The Los Angeles Times|access-date=May 10, 2019|page=38|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/31424515/mae_shumway_enderly_1935/|title=International Club Hears What's in Future|last=|first=|date=December 20, 1935|work=The Los Angeles Times|access-date=May 10, 2019|page=26|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nMinnie Mae Shumway married lumber executive Frederick W. Enderly in Nebraska in 1892. They lived in southern California.<ref name=\":0\" /> They had two children, Richard Curtis Enderly (born 1895) and Venita Grace Enderly (1899-1901).<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/genealogyofshumw00shum|quote=Mae Shumway Enderly.|title=Genealogy of the Shumway Family in the United States|last=|first=|date=1909|publisher=T.A. Wright|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/genealogyofshumw00shum/page/108 108]|language=en}}</ref> Her son married dancer [[Pearl Eaton]] in 1931.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/20179789/18_may_31_pearl_eaton_to_mary_richard/|title=Member of Eaton Sister Trio to Wed|last=|first=|date=May 18, 1931|work=The Los Angeles Times|access-date=May 10, 2019|page=30|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/dayswedancedstor00trav|url-access=registration|quote=Dick Enderly grave.|title=The Days We Danced: The Story of My Theatrical Family from Florenz Ziegfeld to Arthur Murray and Beyond|last=Travis|first=Doris Eaton|date=2003|publisher=University of Oklahoma Press|year=|isbn=9780806199504|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/dayswedancedstor00trav/page/162 162]-163|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Enderly, Mae Shumway}}\n[[Category:1871 births]]\n[[Category:People from Galesburg, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Vaudeville performers]]\n[[Category:Harpists]]\n[[Category:American women in World War I]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Mae Shumway Enderly\n| image              = MaeShumwayEnderly1916.png\n| alt                = Mae Shumway Enderly, dressed in a Norwegian bridal costume, from a 1916 publication.\n| caption            = Mae Shumway Enderly, dressed in a Norwegian bridal costume from a 1916 publication.\n| birth_name         = Minnie Mae Shumway\n| birth_date         = October 30, 1871\n| birth_place        = Galesburg, Illinois\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = American\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = harpist, entertainer\n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = lyceum circuit, Chautauquas, vaudeville\n| notable_works      = \n}}\n\n'''Mae Shumway Enderly''' (October 30, 1871 \u2013 after May 1943<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/31425361/mae_shumway_enderly_1943/|title=Internationalists Plan Luncheon|last=|first=|date=June 13, 1943|work=The Los Angeles Times|access-date=May 10, 2019|page=63|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>) was an American clubwoman, harpist and entertainer on the lyceum platform, the [[Chautauqua]] circuit, and the [[vaudeville]] stage.\n\n== Early life ==\nMinnie Mae Shumway was born in [[Galesburg, Illinois]], the daughter of Stephen Burroughs Shumway and Lydia Jane Streeter Shumway.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/historyofwestern03shum|q